<pb n="iii">
<preface>
<caption r="gothic">Preface</caption>
<p><hi r="smcap">How</hi> active, longeval and fascinating, is hope; the accidents,
reverses and misfortunes of today but invigorate
it, and tomorrow it will be painting brighter goals, in
all the colors of the rainbow, or embellishing the desert, where
it faded yesterday, with the mirage. It follows but never comes
up with the horizon; and when, at the end of its cable tow, it has
reached the bourn, it is then, to many, so seductive in enchantment
that death, in the hour of its triumph, is confused by the garlands
hope wreaths upon the brow of faith.</p>
<p>Beguiled by this alluring vision, I have been seduced into
the difficult, yet pleasing labors of writing verse, a small collection
of which I am exposing to the consideration of the public, before
I have acquired the skill of a novice; who, I am sure, could have
done better, with less effort; and who will, perhaps, upon reviewng
my work, blush derisively at my poverty of thought and vagueness
of expression; such is his pleasure.</p>
<p>It is enough for me to indulge the fancy that an asylum survives
for him who is seduced by the muses, in the lenitive passions
of those, whose love for the beautiful, causes them to tolerate
its worshipers; whose affections for the esthetic, make them
partial to its vassals and whose loftiness of character and charity
of spirit impel them to be lenient where they might be rash, and
just where they might yield to malice; and who, in the exercise
of these happy virtues, do not forget that the daisy comes as
sweet from the fallow as the rose from the garden.</p>
<p>In selecting a name for this poor work, I have, perchance,
done violence to the sensitive feelings of many zealous partizans
of the art of composition, who have, with the usurpation common
to squatter sovereigns, fenced off the domain of poesy, as an
exclusive sporting ground for themselves, where trespassers, such
as I am, are commanded to &ldquo;Keep off the grass.&rdquo; To all such I
would like to say that the name is not chosen because the composition,
for which it stands, is metrical; but rather because I am
a member of that unhappy race of people which are treated as
<pb n="iv">
alien enemies in the land of their nativity, and the victim of that
tyrannous public opinion which makes in them and me, what were
commendable in others, a bar to advancement; and since this
inclement public opinion has barred us from pursuing those civic
pursuits that distinguish the civilian from the savage, and the
savage from the brute, may I not call this little volume &ldquo;Lyrics of
the Under World&rdquo;?</p>
<p>The piece, &ldquo;My Country,&rdquo; is but a fanciful flight of hope from
conditions that are to what ought to be the scope of one's environment
in a country whose underlying principles are said to be,
&ldquo;Equal rights to all, special benefits to none.&rdquo; And, since &ldquo;My
Country&rdquo; is a creature of fancy, may it not be palmed off on the
uninitiated as verse, if not poetry? Those of my fellows who
upbraid me for indulging the fancy, together with those who would
eliminate me under the doctrine, &ldquo;This is a white man's country,&rdquo;
will not, I hope, further deprive me from enjoying through the
imagination what seems to be impossible as a matter of fact.</p>
<p>If these truths are not self&hyphen;evident, but false: &ldquo;That all men
are created equal; that they are endowed by their Creator with
certain unalienable rights; that among these rights are life, liberty
and the pursuit of happiness,&rdquo; let me at least hold them among the
things imaginable. I cannot abandon the position that this is my
country.</p>
<p>There is, I think, enough in the overt acts of some of the
worshipers of the idol, Color, to justify the &ldquo;Lines to Caste,&rdquo;
until a master comes, who will give the subject its proper treatment.
&ldquo;The Jaunt&rdquo; is mere jargon, thrown in to take the place of
&ldquo;The Black Knight,&rdquo; a poem I had intended for this collection,
but which I prefer not to publish at this time. I may say, however,
that in writing &ldquo;The Jaunt&rdquo; I was trying to build a continued
discourse in sonnets, and failed utterly with the soliloquy of age.</p>
<p>Of the other subjects of this collection I prefer to say nothing,
since the reader, a better judge of their merits and demerits
than I am, will render a decision for hlmself.</p>
<p>I would like, however, to thank my two friends, Dr. W. A.
Scott, the publisher, and Hon. W. E. Mollison, who have condescended,
the one to publish the book and the other to write its
introduction, for the encouragement they gave me in my labors.
<pb n="v">
They are the only two college graduates, among my many acquaintances,
who did not think it humiliating to themselves to
recognize me, whom abject poverty during my youth and early
manhood deprived of the benefits of school training.</p>
<p>As to the illustrations, I give &ldquo;Sam in Sleepy Corner&rdquo; the
place of honor, because he is an old companion of mine who
used to sit with me while I munched my food on the curb, or was
kicked into the gutter by the haughty and proud for intruding upon
the public thoroughfare. And yet I am free to say that there is
as much happiness upon the curb as there is in the palace, and
that I haven't had a happy day since I left it. But&mdash;
<l>I've heard so much of poesy, of art,</l>
<l>And mystic things, the plumed wings of thought,</l>
<l>Which none but genius has; none but genius ought</l>
<l>Prime for gay fancy's flight, of awe I start</l>
<l>Amazed! yet motive moved, by buoyant heart</l>
<l>I'd labor where the nobler souls have wrought;</l>
<l>But when I would I'm told, for me 'tis naught</l>
<l>To strive, since neither muse nor art takes part</l>
<l>Where spirit 's dull; yet may I not, beguiled</l>
<l>By no incentive but the soul's flood swell,</l>
<l>Aheave like high tides when the seas run wild,</l>
<l>Awake a passion note, since that strange spell,</l>
<l>Love and not art's the suasive soul of song,</l>
<l>Genius, but labor toiling late and long.</l></p>
<p>I am indebted to my son, Richard Henry Beadle, for the
photographic illustrations, and to Mr. Boon for the cartoon, that
appear in this book.</p>
<p>I entertain for the children of my fancy a fond solicitude, I
part with them with a feeling akin to pain lest they will not give
you as much pleasure, dear reader, in their perusal as I found in
their creation.</p>
<p>If it were not out of place for me to commend them to you I
would like to say a good word for Eulelia, Alice, Iona, Sam and
the others. As it is I but consign them to your consideration
without a word further than subscribing myself,</p>
<signed>YOURS truly, S. A. BEADLE.</signed></preface>
<pb n="vi">
<preface>
<caption r="gothic">Introduction</caption>
<p><hi r="smcap">It</hi> was Abraham Lincoln who said, &ldquo;God Almighty must have
loved the common people, or he would not have made so
many of them.&rdquo; It is not often that the bard makes any
effort to sing the songs of the lowly. The poet is prone to pay
court to the gods who dwell upon Olympus, rather than the delvers
in mines or the fellers of the forest. The author of this book has
seen lifein all of its phases. From the humblest of beginnings, he
has reached heights not dreamed of in his boyhood; has measured
swords with the best and master spirits of his age, and has held
his own among them. His heart must beat in unison with the
sufferings as well as the hopes and aspirations for such as are
not &ldquo;brother to the ox.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Many of these poems voice for the first time the dreams
and hopes of this Under&hyphen;World; many of them have in the lines
glint of real genius, and while our author has not ridden Pegassus
like the Centaur, even Jupiter has nodded at times. Our author's
contribution to the literature of his people and his time will be
more appreciated as the years roll by.</p>
<p>He has placed all of us under lasting obligations to him for
having opened these new vistas into the hearts and souls of the
simple folk whose songs he sings with such consummate grace
and simple beauty.</p>
<p>Mr. Beadle has written many charming verses in earlier
years, many of them show sparks of poetic fire&mdash;but none come
up to the sustained height reached and kept in &ldquo;Lyrics of the
Under World.&rdquo;</p>
<signed>W. E. MOLLISON.</signed></preface>
<pb n="1">
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200265018</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Beadle, Samuel Alfred<sombiog>232</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead>MY COUNTRY.</mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200265018</ID><A1>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</A1><T1>MY COUNTRY.</T1><PBL>W. A. Scott</PBL><Y1>1912</Y1><T2>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</attpoet><attidref>C2040182</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>C2040182</attidref><attdbase>African-American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>MY COUNTRY.</mainhead><volhead>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1912</attpubn1><attpubn2>1912</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>232</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">My</hi> Country God bless thee! God bless thee, my home!
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">With harvest and plenty, thy dark fertile loam;
</l><l ln="3        ">The brooklet that bickers from hills far above,
</l><l ln="4        ">And dances and dallies through vales that I love,
</l><l ln="5        ">Go purling on, may it, the sun on its sheen,
</l><l ln="6        ">The cress and the fern on its banks growing green,
</l><l ln="7        ">The mead ever verdant where graze gentle kine,
</l><l ln="8        ">And wide roam the herds of my neighbor and mine.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="9        ">Thou dearer and grander than all other earth,
</l><l ln="10      ">With clime sweet and balmy, fair land of my birth;
</l><l ln="11      ">May valiant thy youth grow, more stalwart, more brave,
</l><l ln="12      ">Till ne'er a poor laggard, nor coward, nor slave
</l><l ln="13      ">Is seen in thy valleys, nor met on thy hills,
</l><l ln="14      ">Where babbles the brook, or the bright dew distills.
</l><l ln="15      ">Oh, Country of mine! may thy humblest son be
</l><l ln="16      ">Ever true to thy genius, &ldquo;brave, happy and free.&rdquo;</l></stanza>
<pb n="3">
<stanza><l ln="17      ">May palsied the hand grow that strikes not for thee,
</l><l ln="18      ">When traitors would spoil thee, thou land of the free;
</l><l ln="19      ">And the alien who dares to invade thy domain,
</l><l ln="20      ">By the sword let him fall, and from sleep with the slain
</l><l ln="21      ">Let him never awake in the morning to greet
</l><l ln="22      ">The daisies that bloom o'er his dank winding sheet;
</l><l ln="23      ">And freedom, my Country's great boon to the world,
</l><l ln="24      ">Let me die on the day that thy banners are furled.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="25      ">I love thee, adore thee, my Country, I do;
</l><l ln="26      ">Thy faults, though, are many, &ldquo;in pulpit and pew,&rdquo;
</l><l ln="27      ">The work of the vicious, the mean and the vain,
</l><l ln="28      ">Who, vile in their motive and weak in their brain,
</l><l ln="29      ">Forget that the law is the strength of the brave,
</l><l ln="30      ">And the man who would break it worse than a slave.
</l><l ln="31      ">But thou art my Country, still grand and sublime,
</l><l ln="32      ">The noblest in genius, the fairest in clime.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>
<pb n="5">
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200265019</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Beadle, Samuel Alfred<sombiog>232</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead>THE HAVEN OF THE LEES.</mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200265019</ID><A1>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</A1><T1>THE HAVEN OF THE LEES.</T1><PBL>W. A. Scott</PBL><Y1>1912</Y1><T2>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</attpoet><attidref>C2040183</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>C2040183</attidref><attdbase>African-American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>THE HAVEN OF THE LEES.</mainhead><volhead>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1912</attpubn1><attpubn2>1912</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>232</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">Love</hi> is homeless in a palace and in company is lone;
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">She's a vagabond in riches, and a vassal on a throne,
</l><l ln="3        ">In the gilded halls of fortune, on the airy heights of fame,
</l><l ln="4        ">If she's unresuscitated by the husbandman or dame.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="5        ">Love's at home within the hovel, on the curb or in the den,
</l><l ln="6        ">With the highest or the lowest, in the varied walks of men,
</l><l ln="7        ">When they feel the animation of her bouyancy and zeal,
</l><l ln="8        ">Welling big with exultation in the glory of their weal.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="9        ">Love is all there is of heaven. It's the Eden gained by those
</l><l ln="10      ">Who, pursuing art and fortune, loved humanity and rose
</l><l ln="11      ">By the aid they've given others; through this jewel of the soul
</l><l ln="12      ">Leading many wayward brothers to the mead of honor's goal.</l></stanza>
<pb n="6">
<stanza><l ln="13      ">Love's a pleasure to the farmer, and his beaming, lucky star,
</l><l ln="14      ">When at eve he comes returning from his work in fields afar;
</l><l ln="15      ">When his spouse awaits his coming with the grace&hyphen;enthroned brow,
</l><l ln="16      ">Paying homage to his courage, giving honor to his plough.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="17      ">Never knight was half so gallant, never man was half so brave
</l><l ln="18      ">When he greets her in the gloaming as his wife and not his slave,
</l><l ln="19      ">When he gives his steed the bridle, when he flings aside the flail,
</l><l ln="20      ">To assist her in the milking and to bear for her the pail.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="21      ">Love is outraged in the pulpit when the lord presiding there
</l><l ln="22      ">Overlooks the man in homespun for the opulent and fair;
</l><l ln="23      ">For the dazzle of the jewels and the jingle of the coin,
</l><l ln="24      ">Which the nabob, suave and guileful, from the common herd purloin.</l></stanza>
<pb n="7">
<stanza><l ln="25      ">Love's a burden to a princess and a trifle to a throne;
</l><l ln="26      ">For the glory of a monarch is a heart of brass and stone;
</l><l ln="27      ">Else diplomacy would famish and intrigue and guile would wane,
</l><l ln="28      ">In the arms of ease and pleasure, find the certain way to shame.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="29      ">Love's a weakness to a soldier, and this fickle slave of fame
</l><l ln="30      ">Better serves ambition's mandate when the carnage is his aim;
</l><l ln="31      ">But to sailors love's a beacon, beaming bright across the seas,
</l><l ln="32      ">To the glory of the passage, to The Haven of the Lees.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>
<pb n="10">
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200265020</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Beadle, Samuel Alfred<sombiog>232</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead>EULELIA.</mainhead> <attbytes>4Kb</attbytes><volhead>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200265020</ID><A1>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</A1><T1>EULELIA.</T1><PBL>W. A. Scott</PBL><Y1>1912</Y1><T2>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</attpoet><attidref>C2040184</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>C2040184</attidref><attdbase>African-American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>EULELIA.</mainhead><volhead>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>4Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1912</attpubn1><attpubn2>1912</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>232</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">Last</hi> night I lay dozing
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">When in there came,
</l><l ln="3        ">And sat beside me, posing,
</l><l ln="4        ">One whom I claim
</l><l ln="5        ">Is neat, and sweet, and dutiful,
</l><l ln="6        ">Bewitching, too, and beautiful,
</l><l ln="7        ">Superbly grand in charm;
</l><l ln="8        ">The glory of her jetty eyes,
</l><l ln="9        ">The taper of her form,
</l><l ln="10      ">Its taction and its guise&mdash;
</l><l ln="11      ">But then I mustn't tell
</l><l ln="12      ">Of that delightful swell
</l><l ln="13      ">Of breast against my own;
</l><l ln="14      ">Her touch of lips to mine,
</l><l ln="15      ">Like Hebe's nectar wine,
</l><l ln="16      ">Revived, refreshed and blessed me&mdash;
</l><l ln="17      ">And still I mustn't tell
</l><l ln="18      ">How that delightful swell
</l><l ln="19      ">Of heart of hers, to soul of mine,
</l><l ln="20      ">To mine, to mine, to mine!
</l><l ln="21      ">Was like the flow of Hebe's wine
</l><l ln="22      ">Upon a famished tongue.</l></stanza>
<pb n="11">
<stanza><l ln="23      ">Waking, from dream, I found thee,
</l><l ln="24      ">Too prone to pose
</l><l ln="25      ">And others draw around thee,
</l><l ln="26      ">And me with those
</l><l ln="27      ">To taunt with airy flirting,
</l><l ln="28      ">Too happy thou, in hurting,
</l><l ln="29      ">Breaking the heart of me.
</l><l ln="30      ">Eulelia, doth thou know thy crime,
</l><l ln="31      ">Coquettish butchery,
</l><l ln="32      ">Hath but my spirit charmed to lime&mdash;
</l><l ln="33      ">But then I mustn't tell
</l><l ln="34      ">How cursed art thou and fell,
</l><l ln="35      ">Locked in my rival's arms;
</l><l ln="36      ">His touch of lips to thine,
</l><l ln="37      ">A plague and curse to mine,
</l><l ln="38      ">Doth demonize thee, dear;
</l><l ln="39      ">So hence I mustn't dwell
</l><l ln="40      ">On thought of thee, nor tell
</l><l ln="41      ">How his lips touched to thine make brine
</l><l ln="42      ">Of them for mine, for mine,
</l><l ln="43      ">For mine, for mine, for mine!
</l><l ln="44      ">Make brine of thine for mine.</l></stanza>
<pb n="12">
<stanza><l ln="45      ">Eulelia, I'd be sleeping,
</l><l ln="46      ">For then it seems
</l><l ln="47      ">My old thought dome is keeping
</l><l ln="48      ">Tab on happy themes,
</l><l ln="49      ">Of one so rare, so beautiful,
</l><l ln="50      ">With grace so sweet, immutable,
</l><l ln="51      ">And like a Fay's concerned,
</l><l ln="52      ">I can but fancy, love, that she
</l><l ln="53      ">Is thine own self returned
</l><l ln="54      ">With Hebe's cup for me&mdash;
</l><l ln="55      ">But why should I disclose,
</l><l ln="56      ">What charm dispels my throes&mdash;
</l><l ln="57      ">Like Nepenthes' spell 's the heave
</l><l ln="58      ">Of thy fond breast to mine;
</l><l ln="59      ">So charming, rare, divine!
</l><l ln="60      ">That is, so it seems,
</l><l ln="61      ">When I am lost in dream,
</l><l ln="62      ">My day dream's happy theme,
</l><l ln="63      ">That captive holds the heart of mine,
</l><l ln="64      ">Of mine, of mine, of mine!
</l><l ln="65      ">That captive holds the heart of mine,
</l><l ln="66      ">In vassalage to thine.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>
<pb n="14">
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200265021</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Beadle, Samuel Alfred<sombiog>232</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead>LINES TO CASTE.</mainhead> <attbytes>7Kb</attbytes><volhead>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200265021</ID><A1>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</A1><T1>LINES TO CASTE.</T1><PBL>W. A. Scott</PBL><Y1>1912</Y1><T2>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</attpoet><attidref>C2040185</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>C2040185</attidref><attdbase>African-American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>LINES TO CASTE.</mainhead><volhead>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>7Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1912</attpubn1><attpubn2>1912</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>232</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">The</hi> things I love I may not touch,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;But kiss the hand that shackles bring;
</l><l ln="3        ">The thraldom of my soul is such
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;I can but nurse my thongs and sing,
</l><l ln="5        ">&indent;&indent;And hope and pray that destiny
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;&indent;Will somehow yet unfetter me.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="7        ">I simply trust fate as I ought,
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;While hate defames, malice reviles,
</l><l ln="9        ">And so distorts the public thought
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;That even innocence defiles
</l><l ln="11      ">&indent;&indent;All who are not adjudged by caste,
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;&indent;Superior and nobly classed.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="13      ">I may not ponder here nor muse,
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;Nor let the plain truth designate
</l><l ln="15      ">The things it would. The hangman's noose
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;Unmans, deters, doth reinstate
</l><l ln="17      ">&indent;&indent;The inquisition and its hell
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;&indent;Of terror, tyrannous and fell.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="19      ">Oh! that thou'd grant me grace, despair,
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;My dread, my sore distress, my pain,
</l><l ln="21      ">Or I could breathe some form of prayer,
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;Or might some suasive word obtain,
</l><l ln="23      ">&indent;&indent;Through which to move to clemency
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;&indent;The iron hand that shackles me.</l></stanza>
<pb n="15">
<stanza><l ln="25      ">Fanciful thought; I must not hope,
</l><l ln="26      ">&indent;Nor question prejudice and hate;
</l><l ln="27      ">For they who read my horoscope
</l><l ln="28      ">&indent;Say that the stars which rule my fate
</l><l ln="29      ">&indent;&indent;Designed me for vile tyranny,
</l><l ln="30      ">&indent;&indent;And plunder while they fetter me.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="31      ">They bid me grovel, squirm and whine,
</l><l ln="32      ">&indent;Nor strive against vile calumny;
</l><l ln="33      ">And vain the thought that would decline
</l><l ln="34      ">&indent;Submission to such tyranny;
</l><l ln="35      ">&indent;&indent;For like a wild beast from its lair,
</l><l ln="36      ">&indent;&indent;The state doth hound me to despair.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="37      ">My fancy, sure, revives at times,
</l><l ln="38      ">&indent;Soars, but to beat its weary wings
</l><l ln="39      ">Against a bar, that basely limes
</l><l ln="40      ">&indent;Me in my hope; vilest of things,
</l><l ln="41      ">&indent;&indent;So dire, so fell, but strong my prison
</l><l ln="42      ">&indent;&indent;Hope to escape it is derision.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="43      ">And yet there often comes to me,
</l><l ln="44      ">&indent;I know not how, from whence nor where;
</l><l ln="45      ">But comes the thought perpetually,
</l><l ln="46      ">&indent;That justice is not deft to prayer.
</l><l ln="47      ">&indent;&indent;Though it seems barren, yet for me,
</l><l ln="48      ">&indent;&indent;With good is pregnant destiny.</l></stanza>
<pb n="16">
<stanza><l ln="49      ">Then wherefore should my soul repine,
</l><l ln="50      ">&indent;Why be disconsolate and sad;
</l><l ln="51      ">All things are well in Fate's design,
</l><l ln="52      ">&indent;Nor great, nor small, nor good, nor bad
</l><l ln="53      ">&indent;&indent;Has aught to boast of o'er the clay,
</l><l ln="54      ">&indent;&indent;Tyranny plunders, day by day.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="55      ">Fret not, dear soul, whene'r the proud,
</l><l ln="56      ">&indent;The haughty proud, would press you hard.
</l><l ln="57      ">Have they so far subdued the shroud,
</l><l ln="58      ">&indent;That clay can now assume the God?
</l><l ln="59      ">&indent;&indent;Whate'er its form, or hue, or clan,
</l><l ln="60      ">&indent;&indent;Clay's not the measure of the man.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="61      ">The cup where dazzles bright the wine
</l><l ln="62      ">&indent;Was in some distant day and clime
</l><l ln="63      ">Crysalis of a soul like thine;
</l><l ln="64      ">&indent;There spirit, daring, once did climb,
</l><l ln="65      ">&indent;&indent;There dwelt and thought itself a god&mdash;
</l><l ln="66      ">&indent;&indent;'Twas but a tenant of the sod.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="67      ">Who is so great among mankind,
</l><l ln="68      ">&indent;His infancy knew not the womb;
</l><l ln="69      ">And, coming thence, still is not blind,
</l><l ln="70      ">&indent;To wombed life, as he the tomb
</l><l ln="71      ">&indent;&indent;Enfolds within its dank embrace,
</l><l ln="72      ">&indent;Whate'er his prowess, clan or race.</l></stanza>
<pb n="17">
<stanza><l ln="73      ">And who's so small that, should he fall,
</l><l ln="74      ">&indent;Jehovah takes no note of him?
</l><l ln="75      ">Though he be spurned by kings, and all
</l><l ln="76      ">&indent;Who frown men down with visage grim,
</l><l ln="77      ">&indent;&indent;Methinks he'll be as grand in clay
</l><l ln="78      ">&indent;&indent;As he who tortures him today.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="79      ">I know not why I live or die,
</l><l ln="80      ">&indent;Nor why of me the Lord should reck,
</l><l ln="81      ">When like the bruis'd reed prone I lie,
</l><l ln="82      ">&indent;The tyrant's heel upon my neck;
</l><l ln="83      ">&indent;&indent;I simply know that Caste is blind,
</l><l ln="84      ">&indent;&indent;And that its hope is vicious mind.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="85      ">Because God loves He doth chastise,
</l><l ln="86      ">&indent;And makes another race the rod;
</l><l ln="87      ">Then let the chasten race be wise
</l><l ln="88      ">&indent;And know the lash is not the God;
</l><l ln="89      ">&indent;&indent;'Tis not the rod's; chastisement is
</l><l ln="90      ">&indent;&indent;Eternally and justly His.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="91      ">We have forgot our own household,
</l><l ln="92      ">&indent;To take our tribute to the strong&mdash;
</l><l ln="93      ">The willing vassal, young or old,
</l><l ln="94      ">&indent;Deserve chastisement late and long;
</l><l ln="95      ">&indent;&indent;And ours is but the well&hyphen;earned hell
</l><l ln="96      ">&indent;&indent;Of wanton, faithless infidel.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>
<pb n="19">
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200265022</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Beadle, Samuel Alfred<sombiog>232</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead>THE LOVE THAT WOULD NOT KEEP.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200265022</ID><A1>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</A1><T1>THE LOVE THAT WOULD NOT KEEP.</T1><PBL>W. A. Scott</PBL><Y1>1912</Y1><T2>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</attpoet><attidref>C2040186</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>C2040186</attidref><attdbase>African-American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>THE LOVE THAT WOULD NOT KEEP.</mainhead><volhead>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1912</attpubn1><attpubn2>1912</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>232</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">We've</hi> reached diverging paths, dear heart,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">'Tis pity, but 'tis true, we part;
</l><l ln="3        ">It may be thine, it may be mine;
</l><l ln="4        ">But truly the fault seems thine.
</l><l ln="5        ">But place it, dear, just where you will,
</l><l ln="6        ">The fault, let it be mine.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="7        ">However deep the wound, dear heart,
</l><l ln="8        ">Or slight, eternally we part,
</l><l ln="9        ">No matter now who is to blame,
</l><l ln="10      ">No matter who must weep,
</l><l ln="11      ">The cruel fate that severed us;
</l><l ln="12      ">The love that would not keep.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="13      ">I long for rest, the quiet rest
</l><l ln="14      ">Of home, and peace, and happiness,
</l><l ln="15      ">That wedded hearts presage, 'tis mine
</l><l ln="16      ">To know the emptiness of thine,
</l><l ln="17      ">The jealousy of fickle heart
</l><l ln="18      ">To which thy fears incline.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="19      ">No longer now I would conceal,
</l><l ln="20      ">The blight, the pain, the curse I feel;
</l><l ln="21      ">The misery you know, and yet,
</l><l ln="22      ">Dear heart, I would forget,
</l><l ln="23      ">The cruelties of nuptial ties,
</l><l ln="24      ">The fatal day we met.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>
<pb n="23">
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200265023</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Beadle, Samuel Alfred<sombiog>232</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead>THE DEED VS. ASSESSMENT ROLLS.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200265023</ID><A1>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</A1><T1>THE DEED VS. ASSESSMENT ROLLS.</T1><PBL>W. A. Scott</PBL><Y1>1912</Y1><T2>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</attpoet><attidref>C2040187</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>C2040187</attidref><attdbase>African-American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>THE DEED VS. ASSESSMENT ROLLS.</mainhead><volhead>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1912</attpubn1><attpubn2>1912</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>232</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">The</hi> real estate assessment roll
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Would be but plundering per se,
</l><l ln="3        ">If still the courts did not control
</l><l ln="4        ">And hold that deeds convey the fee.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="5        ">Like holy writ and creed of fane,
</l><l ln="6        ">Heart to heart, and cheek by jowl,
</l><l ln="7        ">The courts their virtues still retain,
</l><l ln="8        ">And keep the deed above the roll.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="9        ">By it they stand, by it they fall,
</l><l ln="10      ">What e'er the ambiguities,
</l><l ln="11      ">They look to its intrinsic call,
</l><l ln="12      ">For metes and bounds efficiencies.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="13      ">And if they should consult a clue,
</l><l ln="14      ">The deed itself must furnish that;
</l><l ln="15      ">That rolls are not the points of view,
</l><l ln="16      ">The courts stand uniformly &ldquo;pat.&rdquo;</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>
<pb n="27">
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200265024</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Beadle, Samuel Alfred<sombiog>232</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead>IRENE.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200265024</ID><A1>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</A1><T1>IRENE.</T1><PBL>W. A. Scott</PBL><Y1>1912</Y1><T2>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</attpoet><attidref>C2040188</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>C2040188</attidref><attdbase>African-American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>IRENE.</mainhead><volhead>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1912</attpubn1><attpubn2>1912</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>232</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">In</hi> the mid year's afternoon,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Time and nature blushing June,
</l><l ln="3        ">I go calling on my bonny girl, Irene,
</l><l ln="4        ">And I meet her 'neath a bower,
</l><l ln="5        ">Where the roses all a&hyphen;flower,
</l><l ln="6        ">Shed their fragrance in a deluge on Irene.
</l><l ln="7        ">In all the world I know,
</l><l ln="8        ">There's nothing just like this;
</l><l ln="9        ">'Tis happiness, 'tis bliss!
</l><l ln="10      ">And it delights me so;
</l><l ln="11      ">There's nothing just like this,
</l><l ln="12      ">In all the world I know.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="13      ">Hers is blissful company,
</l><l ln="14      ">And I'm happy, don't you see,
</l><l ln="15      ">When I'm calling on my bonny girl, Irene;
</l><l ln="16      ">In the haunts that harbor her,
</l><l ln="17      ">There a scent of lavender
</l><l ln="18      ">Blends its sweetness with the roses for Irene;
</l><l ln="19      ">In all the world I know,
</l><l ln="20      ">There's nothing just like this;
</l><l ln="21      ">'Tis happiness, 'tis bliss!
</l><l ln="22      ">And it delights me so;
</l><l ln="23      ">There's nothing just like this,
</l><l ln="24      ">In all the world I know.</l></stanza>
<pb n="28">
<stanza><l ln="25      ">There is magic in her eye,
</l><l ln="26      ">And the Graces seem to vie,
</l><l ln="27      ">In the placing of their glories on Irene,
</l><l ln="28      ">When I fold her in my arms,
</l><l ln="29      ">Captivated by the charms,
</l><l ln="30      ">And the fascinating taction of Irene,
</l><l ln="31      ">In all the world I know,
</l><l ln="32      ">There's nothing just like this;
</l><l ln="33      ">'Tis happiness, 'tis bliss!
</l><l ln="34      ">And it delights me so;
</l><l ln="35      ">There's nothing just like this
</l><l ln="36      ">In all the world I know.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>
<pb n="31">
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200265025</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Beadle, Samuel Alfred<sombiog>232</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead>FORGIVEN.</mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200265025</ID><A1>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</A1><T1>FORGIVEN.</T1><PBL>W. A. Scott</PBL><Y1>1912</Y1><T2>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</attpoet><attidref>C2040189</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>C2040189</attidref><attdbase>African-American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>FORGIVEN.</mainhead><volhead>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1912</attpubn1><attpubn2>1912</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>232</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">I'd</hi> roamed around by no ties bound,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">But fancy's vain and fickle will;
</l><l ln="3        ">Squandered my youth and trampled truth,
</l><l ln="4        ">Beneath my wayward feet, until
</l><l ln="5        ">My carnal heart had taken part
</l><l ln="6        ">In all that pride finds pleasure in,
</l><l ln="7        ">While fathoming the depths of sin.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="8        ">At this vile wantonness, one day
</l><l ln="9        ">I lost my immortality,
</l><l ln="10      ">And stood before the open door
</l><l ln="11      ">Of sheol's grim reality;
</l><l ln="12      ">Brought face to face with death, and grace,
</l><l ln="13      ">Jehovah's loving kindness, spurned,
</l><l ln="14      ">How cravingly to live I yearned.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="15      ">Praying for life, immortal life,
</l><l ln="16      ">I offered what I had in lands,
</l><l ln="17      ">Silver, my gold, the fees I hold,
</l><l ln="18      ">And all the labor of my hands.
</l><l ln="19      ">The decalogue, through fear of God,
</l><l ln="20      ">I vowed to keep; yet none of these
</l><l ln="21      ">The king of terrors could appease.</l></stanza>
<pb n="32">
<stanza><l ln="22      ">At last I prayed for light and said,
</l><l ln="23      ">Show me, O Lord, the way; what Thou
</l><l ln="24      ">Wouldst have me do I'll now pursue;
</l><l ln="25      ">Forgive! Cool thou my fevered brow,
</l><l ln="26      ">Teach me to share my brother's care,
</l><l ln="27      ">To love mankind; and if not me,
</l><l ln="28      ">Bless Thou, O Lord, mine enemy.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="29      ">At this there came a great acclaim,
</l><l ln="30      ">Hosannas from the hills of peace,
</l><l ln="31      ">Angelic throngs broke into songs
</l><l ln="32      ">And Mercy brought me sure surcease
</l><l ln="33      ">Of blighting pain, and o'er again
</l><l ln="34      ">Jehovah reckoned unto me
</l><l ln="35      ">The righteousness of purity.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>
<pb n="35">
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200265026</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Beadle, Samuel Alfred<sombiog>232</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead>THE SHADY SIDE.</mainhead> <attbytes>6Kb</attbytes><volhead>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200265026</ID><A1>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</A1><T1>THE SHADY SIDE.</T1><PBL>W. A. Scott</PBL><Y1>1912</Y1><T2>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</attpoet><attidref>C2040190</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>C2040190</attidref><attdbase>African-American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>THE SHADY SIDE.</mainhead><volhead>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>6Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1912</attpubn1><attpubn2>1912</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>232</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">There</hi>'s something fascinating on life's dark and sombre side,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">When the worn and travel&hyphen;weary seek for rest at even tide;
</l><l ln="3        ">In the shadows where the fallen come to muse on faded hope,
</l><l ln="4        ">Expectancies that vanished like to bubbles blown from soap.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="5        ">If you should reach the shady side of life methinks you'll find,
</l><l ln="6        ">Some who have found the upper world so heartless and unkind,
</l><l ln="7        ">And so disposed to torture with the despotisms there
</l><l ln="8        ">They had to seek the shadows as a refuge from despair.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="9        ">Take him who grubs for fortune in a systematic way,
</l><l ln="10      ">Till &ldquo;biz&rdquo; is rich in promise and responsive in its pay,
</l><l ln="11      ">And faith ascends the zenith lit with hope, his lucky star,
</l><l ln="12      ">And watch him when the nagger plies her repartees that bar.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="13      ">Then see him with the languor and forlorn in all his air,
</l><l ln="14      ">A standing on the curbstone in a semi&hyphen;vacant stare;
</l><l ln="15      ">In pendulous vibrations 'twix the club&hyphen;room and his wife,
</l><l ln="16      ">This a solace, that a nagger, to his swiftly ebbing life.</l></stanza>
<pb n="36">
<stanza><l ln="17      ">The wife is simply nothing if she can't assert her rights;
</l><l ln="18      ">Cannot attend the socials and the musicals of nights,
</l><l ln="19      ">And there forget the promise of our sunny years flown long
</l><l ln="20      ">With the graces of the angels and the eloquence of song.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="21      ">But the wayward, something wiser than your wife, plays on your whim,
</l><l ln="22      ">Veneering all your failures with the glow of triumph's glim,
</l><l ln="23      ">E'er sees in you some greatness, never finds in you a fault,
</l><l ln="24      ">You're every whit par excellence, though brimming full of malt.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="25      ">We cannot help but like them if we dared do otherwise,
</l><l ln="26      ">Their sympathy and fervor would their meaner selves disguise;
</l><l ln="27      ">So far transcend the nagging of our double&hyphen;tongued wives,
</l><l ln="28      ">The nuptials were but prose beside the lyric of our lives.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="29      ">With naggers, life is painful if they do not roar and snort
</l><l ln="30      ">With frenzy and with fury, and the trespass of retort;
</l><l ln="31      ">And club men are so constant in their social thought and air,
</l><l ln="32      ">You just forget deception is the glory reigning there.</l></stanza>
<pb n="37">
<stanza><l ln="33      ">Men know 'tis wrong to wander, that to dissipate is sin,
</l><l ln="34      ">That the dazzle of the harem is the web the evil spin,
</l><l ln="35      ">To inveigle and to plunder, and to deprivate and spoil,
</l><l ln="36      ">But to the flings of nagging wives they make a splendid foil.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="37      ">You may moralize and blame them, you may put them under ban,
</l><l ln="38      ">And scourge them out of Eden, from Beersheba unto Dan;
</l><l ln="39      ">But they'll fly the track at intervals and seek the Shady Side,
</l><l ln="40      ">Though naggers all were angels and with deities allied.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="41      ">A lodge within the fastness of the desert waste, or wild,
</l><l ln="42      ">Is better than the castle hall and palace courts defiled
</l><l ln="43      ">By wielding of the epigram and reign of repartee,
</l><l ln="44      ">Where the housewife's pride and glory is to nag and disagree.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="45      ">Again, take her whose virginhood bloomed on the Sunny Side,
</l><l ln="46      ">Who had no whim unfavored and no wish not satisfied;
</l><l ln="47      ">But loved while young, and loving, took the first mad leap and lost.
</l><l ln="48      ">And see what door will open, and what lord will be her host.</l></stanza>
<pb n="38">
<stanza><l ln="49      ">If she, perchance a mother, friend, should visit you today,
</l><l ln="50      ">Are you not sure you'd drive her and her infant child away;
</l><l ln="51      ">What matron of the sisterhood of elite folks above
</l><l ln="52      ">Would comfort give a wanderer from the sunny haunts of love?</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="53      ">Except, perhaps, they might take him whose purse has golden strings;
</l><l ln="54      ">Or him who has a title to estates and fees and things;
</l><l ln="55      ">Aye! truly they might lord the man who dragged the maiden down,
</l><l ln="56      ">And let him take his pick of hearts from daughters of their own.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="57      ">But she who young in loving took the first mad leap and lost,
</l><l ln="58      ">Must wander forth hereafter, friend, a vagabond at most,
</l><l ln="59      ">Unless she seeks the Shady Side, where high&hyphen;flown hopes are furled,
</l><l ln="60      ">And take her portion and her chance with us of the Under World.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="61      ">And let her not be weary, nor in her soul cast down,
</l><l ln="62      ">We have no social tyrants here who murder with a frown;
</l><l ln="63      ">But noble men and women, too, with souls like open charts,
</l><l ln="64      ">Who take one's measure not from gold, but purposes of heart.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>
<pb n="41">
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200265027</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Beadle, Samuel Alfred<sombiog>232</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead>JOHN MARSHALL'S DIVORCE</mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200265027</ID><A1>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</A1><T1>JOHN MARSHALL'S DIVORCE</T1><PBL>W. A. Scott</PBL><Y1>1912</Y1><T2>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</attpoet><attidref>C2040191</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>C2040191</attidref><attdbase>African-American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>JOHN MARSHALL'S DIVORCE</mainhead><volhead>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1912</attpubn1><attpubn2>1912</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>232</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">Today this cause came to be heard
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;On bill, process and proof;
</l><l ln="3        ">Averments usual, form and word,
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;Prolixity forsooth.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="5        ">John Marshall was complainant's name,
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;Carrie, his wife, defendant,
</l><l ln="7        ">He charged as being wanton dame,
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;To lecher rake intendant.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="9        ">For Carrie loud they called by rote,
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;The &ldquo;Oyez! oyez! oyez,
</l><l ln="11      ">Come into court, come into court,
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;Or you'll be barred, oyez.&rdquo;</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="13      ">If Carrie heard, she heeded not,
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;Default she wholly made,
</l><l ln="15      ">And John has still a spouseless cot,
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;If not a buxom maid</l></stanza>
<pb n="42">
<stanza><l ln="17      ">And having heard what was averred
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;Of Carrie's wanton acts,
</l><l ln="19      ">And finding she had not demurred,
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;The Court reviewed the facts.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="21      ">These marriage ties, the Court believes,
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;Have grown so lax, corrupt,
</l><l ln="23      ">It should and does by fit decrees,
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;Break all the nuptials up.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="25      ">We find the process good and true,
</l><l ln="26      ">&indent;With regular procedure;
</l><l ln="27      ">And on the whole there comes to view
</l><l ln="28      ">&indent;The proofs the facts concede you.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="29      ">Unquestioned those, efficient these,
</l><l ln="30      ">&indent;All costs and fees enforced,
</l><l ln="31      ">The Court now orders and decrees
</l><l ln="32      ">&indent;John Marshall is divorced.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="33      ">Done in the merry month of May,
</l><l ln="34      ">&indent;Year nineteen hundred 'leven,
</l><l ln="35      ">And if you would exact the day,
</l><l ln="36      ">&indent;Know you 'tis twenty&hyphen;seven.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>
<pb n="45">
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200265028</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Beadle, Samuel Alfred<sombiog>232</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead>IF I HAD A MILLION.</mainhead> <attbytes>5Kb</attbytes><volhead>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200265028</ID><A1>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</A1><T1>IF I HAD A MILLION.</T1><PBL>W. A. Scott</PBL><Y1>1912</Y1><T2>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</attpoet><attidref>C2040192</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>C2040192</attidref><attdbase>African-American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>IF I HAD A MILLION.</mainhead><volhead>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>5Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1912</attpubn1><attpubn2>1912</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>232</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">Had</hi> I a million dollars, friend, I don't know what I'd do,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">But now and then I think I'd roam and simply spend a few;
</l><l ln="3        ">Again I think I'd steal away to rural quietude,
</l><l ln="4        ">And spend the rest of life among the simple and the rude.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="5        ">I hardly think with flippancies that I would be imbued,
</l><l ln="6        ">The new club woman and her fad, I know I would elude;
</l><l ln="7        ">Nor should my person be spruced up with dress immaculate;
</l><l ln="8        ">A whole big million I don't think my old pate would inflate.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="9        ">'Tis true, I'd like to slip a cog, and go it wild a bit,
</l><l ln="10      ">My soul aglow with passion for my brother in the pit;
</l><l ln="11      ">Ay! proud to be with commoners, I'd rusticate a&hyphen;while,
</l><l ln="12      ">Nor would I care a cursed thing about the latest style.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="13      ">&ldquo;Old brogan shoes and homespun socks?&rdquo; the very things I need;
</l><l ln="14      ">For too much dress and fashion, sir, would my lithe step impede;
</l><l ln="15      ">An old cord &ldquo;gallus,&rdquo; friend, would hold my breeches on to me,
</l><l ln="16      ">And I'd not care a snap about their bagging at the knee.</l></stanza>
<pb n="46">
<stanza><l ln="17      ">The fine silk plug and Panama are hats I do not need;
</l><l ln="18      ">I'd rather poise my head beneath the straw of Dixie's mead;
</l><l ln="19      ">Indeed, my friend, I'd be content beneath a brimless cap,
</l><l ln="20      ">To sport it with the urching all, a jolly, romping chap.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="21      ">With them I'd like to take just now a little bit of ease,
</l><l ln="22      ">A&hyphen;lounging where I used to, sir, beneath the apple trees,
</l><l ln="23      ">A&hyphen;whittling and a&hyphen;swapping jokes with Bill and Tom and Ned,
</l><l ln="24      ">The while our fancies flit across the lore of trundle bed.</l></stanza>
<pb n="47">
<stanza><l ln="25      ">Yea, over and above it all, this is the simple truth,
</l><l ln="26      ">Had I the coin, and could, I'd spend a million for my youth;
</l><l ln="27      ">Then with my true love I would go a&hyphen;sparking it again,
</l><l ln="28      ">And look the love upon her grace my tongue could ne'er explain.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="29      ">I'd lead her once again, my friend, through old Virginia reel,
</l><l ln="30      ">Salute her there and balance all; again I'd fondly feel
</l><l ln="31      ">The same old bliss so oft I've felt, while swinging corners all,
</l><l ln="32      ">And stepping to the music of the jocund country ball.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="33      ">These things were worth a million to a maimed old chap like me,
</l><l ln="34      ">I'd give it if I could, sir, with a zest of childish glee.
</l><l ln="35      ">Oh! if I could but put away my gout and rheumatiz,
</l><l ln="36      ">And take an old&hyphen;time outing from the pressure of my biz!</l></stanza>
<pb n="48">
<stanza><l ln="37      ">A bonny girl and youth I'd take to Cupid's mystic shrine,
</l><l ln="38      ">That sylvan haunt of Dixie, where the jessamine doth twine;
</l><l ln="39      ">Where lilies, fiant of sweetness, and where ever blows the thyme;
</l><l ln="40      ">Where seasons all are summer and the climate is sublime.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="41      ">The rose aflame of beauty, there drops petals on the sod,
</l><l ln="42      ">To scarlet blush geraniums, and passion flowers nod
</l><l ln="43      ">In breezy swells of zephyrs that strike up the mystic chime,
</l><l ln="44      ">While carol winged minstrels in the glory of their prime.</l></stanza>
<pb n="49">
<stanza><l ln="45      ">If you could take the silver from this hoary pate of mine,
</l><l ln="46      ">And make it so my bouyant youth could never more decline;
</l><l ln="47      ">And bring me back my bonny girl that long&hyphen;lost love again,
</l><l ln="48      ">So vivified she might not feel another touch of pain;</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="49      ">The million dollars you might have, and millions o'er and o'er;
</l><l ln="50      ">Again I'd take my youth and love, and ask for nothing more,
</l><l ln="51      ">As long as we could stroll about the old, familiar ways,
</l><l ln="52      ">And feel the bouyant, throbbing hearts of love and better days.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>
<pb n="53">
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200265029</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Beadle, Samuel Alfred<sombiog>232</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead>THE THORN.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200265029</ID><A1>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</A1><T1>THE THORN.</T1><PBL>W. A. Scott</PBL><Y1>1912</Y1><T2>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</attpoet><attidref>C2040193</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>C2040193</attidref><attdbase>African-American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>THE THORN.</mainhead><volhead>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1912</attpubn1><attpubn2>1912</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>232</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">'Tis</hi> strange that those for whom we care,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;For us so little feel;
</l><l ln="3        ">And those we shun would gladly share
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;So much of service, love and weal,
</l><l ln="5        ">&indent;&indent;So much of life for us.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="6        ">And stranger still, those whom we serve
</l><l ln="7        ">&indent;So slightly hold the deed;
</l><l ln="8        ">And they our acts would best subserve,
</l><l ln="9        ">&indent;So seldom get, so often need
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;&indent;Encouragement from us.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="11      ">Too true it is, they hold the rose
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;And flay us with the thorn;
</l><l ln="13      ">And stranger still, we're foiled by those
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;Our fervent hope is to adorn,
</l><l ln="15      ">&indent;&indent;Our will is but to serve.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>
<pb n="57">
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200265030</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Beadle, Samuel Alfred<sombiog>232</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead>LINES TO IONA.</mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200265030</ID><A1>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</A1><T1>LINES TO IONA.</T1><PBL>W. A. Scott</PBL><Y1>1912</Y1><T2>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</attpoet><attidref>C2040194</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>C2040194</attidref><attdbase>African-American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>LINES TO IONA.</mainhead><volhead>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1912</attpubn1><attpubn2>1912</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>232</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">Had</hi> love an answer to its prayer,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Sweet Iona, I would be there,
</l><l ln="3        ">To solace and caress thee;
</l><l ln="4        ">Had love an answer to its prayer,
</l><l ln="5        ">How truly I wert thine;
</l><l ln="6        ">But love seems prone to go alone,
</l><l ln="7        ">Of first incentives shorn.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="8        ">And thou art far away this eve,
</l><l ln="9        ">And such an eve it is, believe
</l><l ln="10      ">Me Iona, believe!
</l><l ln="11      ">How sorely doth thine absence grieve,
</l><l ln="12      ">What happiness wert mine,
</l><l ln="13      ">Could we now stroll and soul to soul
</l><l ln="14      ">Unbosom and forget.</l></stanza>
<pb n="58">
<stanza><l ln="15      ">Sweet Iona, forget, forget,
</l><l ln="16      ">Unbosom now and freely let
</l><l ln="17      ">Vain, fickle pride depart,
</l><l ln="18      ">Be thou thyself, come let us yet
</l><l ln="19      ">Of love's nepenthe drink,
</l><l ln="20      ">As in the olden and the golden
</l><l ln="21      ">Happy, dreamy days.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="22      ">For this I'd stroll with thee, sweetheart,
</l><l ln="23      ">From all the social world apart,
</l><l ln="24      ">I'd go once more with thee;
</l><l ln="25      ">Nor would I care how keen the dart,
</l><l ln="26      ">Sharp the wit, nor foul the tongue,
</l><l ln="27      ">Of rumor, dear, that fills the ear
</l><l ln="28      ">Of gossipers at large.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="29      ">I'd rather stray, sweetheart, with thee,
</l><l ln="30      ">Than know the sweetest ecstacy,
</l><l ln="31      ">Of elite folks and grand,
</l><l ln="32      ">Nor question I my destiny,
</l><l ln="33      ">Be it but linked with thine;
</l><l ln="34      ">For he lives best who is caressed
</l><l ln="35      ">By the woman whom he loves.</l></stanza>
<pb n="59">
<stanza><l ln="36      ">The moon is at its best tonight,
</l><l ln="37      ">The sky is fair, the stars are bright,
</l><l ln="38      ">The air, bescent'd with flowers,
</l><l ln="39      ">Goes winging by in zephyrs light
</l><l ln="40      ">As Aeolus can blow them;
</l><l ln="41      ">And by the way he winds the lay
</l><l ln="42      ">Of other youths and lassies.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="43      ">It is the hour, the happy time,
</l><l ln="44      ">When lovers strike their sweetest chime
</l><l ln="45      ">Of deep and fervent wooing;
</l><l ln="46      ">When looks are vows, and vows sublime,
</l><l ln="47      ">That ripple into smiles and blend
</l><l ln="48      ">Assenting thought to all they ought,
</l><l ln="49      ">When words were mean expression.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="50      ">And on the border line between
</l><l ln="51      ">The upper and the lower sheen,
</l><l ln="52      ">Of day and mystic night,
</l><l ln="53      ">Our wounded love and pride, I wean,
</l><l ln="54      ">Might find a charm to soothe them,
</l><l ln="55      ">In mending all and blending all
</l><l ln="56      ">Their broken chords of weal.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>
<pb n="61">
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200265031</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Beadle, Samuel Alfred<sombiog>232</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead>WHEN TRUTH COMES HOME.</mainhead> <attbytes>4Kb</attbytes><volhead>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200265031</ID><A1>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</A1><T1>WHEN TRUTH COMES HOME.</T1><PBL>W. A. Scott</PBL><Y1>1912</Y1><T2>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</attpoet><attidref>C2040195</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>C2040195</attidref><attdbase>African-American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>WHEN TRUTH COMES HOME.</mainhead><volhead>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>4Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1912</attpubn1><attpubn2>1912</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>232</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">Once</hi> in a while in the hush of night,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Comes to hope's altar out of the dark,
</l><l ln="3        ">A wanderer seeking light.
</l><l ln="4        ">A wretched waif, in a wretched plight,
</l><l ln="5        ">Comes to hope's altar out of the dark,
</l><l ln="6        ">Once in a while at night.
</l><l ln="7        ">She's not the blond and blue&hyphen;eyed queen,
</l><l ln="8        ">Whom Anglo&hyphen;Saxon bards all sing,
</l><l ln="9        ">With gauzy tresses of flaxen hair,
</l><l ln="10      ">Falling in golden ringlets fair
</l><l ln="11      ">Over a marble bust.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="12      ">But simply stumbling in the dark,
</l><l ln="13      ">Alone o'er desert, waste and wild,
</l><l ln="14      ">She comes a child of the dark;
</l><l ln="15      ">Poor queen, bewildered and beguiled,
</l><l ln="16      ">Deserted, outraged and reviled,
</l><l ln="17      ">She comes a child of the dark
</l><l ln="18      ">Pleading for mercy's pitiful care,
</l><l ln="19      ">Her weary eyes lose their leering light
</l><l ln="20      ">Uplift from their awful dark despair,
</l><l ln="21      ">A wistful beam o'er a luring dream
</l><l ln="22      ">In prayer for charity.</l></stanza>
<pb n="62">
<stanza><l ln="23      ">No powder flash for her has burned,
</l><l ln="24      ">Nor cannon roared, nor boomed for her,
</l><l ln="25      ">Nor sword in scabbard turned,
</l><l ln="26      ">Blood of her bardel chief to spill
</l><l ln="27      ">But all have sought to ruin her,
</l><l ln="28      ">However much she's yearned
</l><l ln="29      ">The aid of power's bristling steel,
</l><l ln="30      ">That shields the pride of Dixie's dame,
</l><l ln="31      ">And keeps her pure; lest she might reel,
</l><l ln="32      ">And every cur that meets with her
</l><l ln="33      ">Might satiate his lust.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="34      ">The waif queen doth in horror drain
</l><l ln="35      ">The dregs of shame, her woeful plight
</l><l ln="36      ">Tells how the iron reign
</l><l ln="37      ">Blights sire and son of Dixie's might
</l><l ln="38      ">Their matron&hyphen;spouse and lassies bright,
</l><l ln="39      ">Their lords of State and fane,
</l><l ln="40      ">In spite of caste, by thraldom's chain.
</l><l ln="41      ">The moral blight which this entails
</l><l ln="42      ">On human soul and human brain,
</l><l ln="43      ">Is like a frightful destiny,
</l><l ln="44      ">In tyranny run mad.</l></stanza>
<pb n="63">
<stanza><l ln="45      ">Alike the lord of wealth and fane,
</l><l ln="46      ">The renegade and plunderer,
</l><l ln="47      ">The libertine inane;
</l><l ln="48      ">When my waif queen appeals to such
</l><l ln="49      ">They lead a dual life with her,
</l><l ln="50      ">And ravish while they feign
</l><l ln="51      ">To be immaculate in creed,
</l><l ln="52      ">In utterance, infallible,
</l><l ln="53      ">Par excellence in deed;
</l><l ln="54      ">The vile and chaste, they foul and waste,
</l><l ln="55      ">In harem and in church.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="56      ">The iron hand her actions tone,
</l><l ln="57      ">And mammon leads to perfidy,
</l><l ln="58      ">Away from all her own,
</l><l ln="59      ">When comes the lordly heir of caste,
</l><l ln="60      ">Triumphant in his lechery,
</l><l ln="61      ">To sow his oats upon
</l><l ln="62      ">The fallow of the Under World;
</l><l ln="63      ">And then at morn, what blasting horn?
</l><l ln="64      ">What banners to the breeze unfurled?
</l><l ln="65      ">He spurns the spouse of his carouse,
</l><l ln="66      ">Murders when truth comes home.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>
<pb n="65">
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200265032</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Beadle, Samuel Alfred<sombiog>232</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead>THE DRIVING OF THE CATTLE HOME.</mainhead> <attbytes>6Kb</attbytes><volhead>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200265032</ID><A1>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</A1><T1>THE DRIVING OF THE CATTLE HOME.</T1><PBL>W. A. Scott</PBL><Y1>1912</Y1><T2>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</attpoet><attidref>C2040196</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>C2040196</attidref><attdbase>African-American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>THE DRIVING OF THE CATTLE HOME.</mainhead><volhead>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>6Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1912</attpubn1><attpubn2>1912</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>232</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">Long</hi> ago, when evening's twilight,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Came vermilion, touched with gold,
</l><l ln="3        ">Save where nature penciled shadows
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;Of a lassie, herd and wold,
</l><l ln="5        ">On the emerald of the meadow,
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;By a pathway to a fold,
</l><l ln="7        ">Came a lassie o'er the heather,
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;Where the sleek kine browse and roam,
</l><l ln="9        ">&indent;Calling of the cattle home.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="10      ">Then I felt a mystic rapture,
</l><l ln="11      ">&indent;I could never all explain;
</l><l ln="12      ">Nor the why my heart a tattoo
</l><l ln="13      ">&indent;Sets to throbbing in my brain.
</l><l ln="14      ">When of nights I watch the embers
</l><l ln="15      ">&indent;Of the yule&hyphen;log glow and wane,
</l><l ln="16      ">Through the long and dreary evenings,
</l><l ln="17      ">&indent;While the ghosts of things that were,
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;O'er the waning embers stir,</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="19      ">There's enchantment full and plenty,
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;Where the cattle roam and feed,
</l><l ln="21      ">In my reminiscent fancy,
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;On the em'rald of the mead;
</l><l ln="23      ">Where the shimmers of the sunset,
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;From the sombre woodlands speed,
</l><l ln="25      ">Fall but brightly on the pathway,
</l><l ln="26      ">&indent;Till it beams a thread of gold,
</l><l ln="27      ">&indent;From the moorland to the fold.</l></stanza>
<pb n="66">
<stanza><l ln="28      ">Now, from out the icy claspings,
</l><l ln="29      ">&indent;Of the sepulcher of years,
</l><l ln="30      ">While the glow of dying embers
</l><l ln="31      ">&indent;On my old hearthstone appears,
</l><l ln="32      ">Comes an angel through the shadows,
</l><l ln="33      ">&indent;Age encumbers with, and clears
</l><l ln="34      ">All the clouds from recollections
</l><l ln="35      ">&indent;Of my truant coming home,
</l><l ln="36      ">&indent;With the lassie through the gloam.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="37      ">But the lassie, heaven bless her,
</l><l ln="38      ">&indent;Went a&hyphen;calling long ago,
</l><l ln="39      ">On a cherub up in glory,
</l><l ln="40      ">&indent;Whom she did but scarcely know.
</l><l ln="41      ">There the angels hold her captive,
</l><l ln="42      ">&indent;Envying her beauty so;
</l><l ln="43      ">But of evenings when they revel,
</l><l ln="44      ">&indent;And I lapse to revery,
</l><l ln="45      ">&indent;She as often visits me.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="46      ">Comes with all her mystic beauty,
</l><l ln="47      ">&indent;Budding on her like the rose,
</l><l ln="48      ">Blowing wild upon the heather,
</l><l ln="49      ">&indent;With a charm of grace that grows
</l><l ln="50      ">On my mem'ry when I'm waking,
</l><l ln="51      ">&indent;In my vision when I doze,
</l><l ln="52      ">With her lobate bust a&hyphen;heaving,
</l><l ln="53      ">&indent;And a scent of lavender,
</l><l ln="54      ">&indent;In the rustic robes of her.</l></stanza>
<pb n="67">
<stanza><l ln="55      ">Then we stroll again, fond lovers,
</l><l ln="56      ">&indent;Through the embers waning glow;
</l><l ln="57      ">Not a crow&hyphen;foot on her visage,
</l><l ln="58      ">&indent;Nor a shadow on my brow;
</l><l ln="59      ">Both as charmed, as free, as happy,
</l><l ln="60      ">&indent;Now within the afterglow,
</l><l ln="61      ">As when first we went a&hyphen;sparking,
</l><l ln="62      ">&indent;Down the verdant hills of loam
</l><l ln="63      ">&indent;Driving of the cattle home.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="64      ">Strolling homeward in the gloaming,
</l><l ln="65      ">&indent;'Twix a nap and fancy's flight,
</l><l ln="66      ">As the time upon the dial
</l><l ln="67      ">&indent;Loiters towards the noon of night,
</l><l ln="68      ">And the yule&hyphen;log, gray with ashes,
</l><l ln="69      ">&indent;Smoulders to a leering light,
</l><l ln="70      ">And the cerfew bells of glory
</l><l ln="71      ">&indent;Call the lassie back from me,
</l><l ln="72      ">&indent;Through the hazy reverie.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="73      ">Let the yule&hyphen;log's embers smoulder,
</l><l ln="74      ">&indent;And the angels sportive be,
</l><l ln="75      ">While I sit in sleepy corner,
</l><l ln="76      ">&indent;Nap and dream, sweetheart, of thee;
</l><l ln="77      ">Till the rare and brilliant glory
</l><l ln="78      ">&indent;Of the by&hyphen;gones comes to me,
</l><l ln="79      ">And we stroll, the happy lovers,
</l><l ln="80      ">&indent;Hearts a&hyphen;welling with the swells
</l><l ln="81      ">&indent;Of the tinkling cattle bells.</l></stanza>
<pb n="68">
<stanza><l ln="82      ">Ah, the subtle, pleasing fiction
</l><l ln="83      ">&indent;That is bundled up in dreams,
</l><l ln="84      ">Dreams that lead us on and ravish
</l><l ln="85      ">&indent;With their sweet, alluring themes,
</l><l ln="86      ">Diorames bright and sparkling
</l><l ln="87      ">&indent;Like to beacons over streams,
</l><l ln="88      ">Or like some mirage, oasis
</l><l ln="89      ">&indent;Of Sahara, oft they come
</l><l ln="90      ">&indent;With their mystic polycrome</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>
<pb n="71">
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200265033</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Beadle, Samuel Alfred<sombiog>232</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead>ONWARD.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200265033</ID><A1>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</A1><T1>ONWARD.</T1><PBL>W. A. Scott</PBL><Y1>1912</Y1><T2>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</attpoet><attidref>C2040197</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>C2040197</attidref><attdbase>African-American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>ONWARD.</mainhead><volhead>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1912</attpubn1><attpubn2>1912</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>232</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">Let</hi> us weld the bond of union,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Make the standard stronger still,
</l><l ln="3        ">Till the fellowship of brothers,
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;All our dreams of hope fulfill;
</l><l ln="5        ">Let us purge ourselves of error,
</l><l ln="6        ">Spurn the villain from our midst,
</l><l ln="7        ">Bring the shrine of honor nearer
</l><l ln="8        ">Christian consciousness of heart.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="9        ">Let us build a shrine to virtue,
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;Where the graces may sojourn;
</l><l ln="11      ">Sacred to their cause forever,
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;There let honor's incense burn;
</l><l ln="13      ">On that altar let religion,
</l><l ln="14      ">Such as Christ has given us,
</l><l ln="15      ">Be the sole inspiring mission
</l><l ln="16      ">Of a nobler brotherhood.</l></stanza>
<pb n="72">
<stanza><l ln="17      ">Let us strive, and striving, conquer,
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;First of all our erring selves;
</l><l ln="19      ">Then we'll hope, and hoping, labor,
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;As one in the quarry delves,
</l><l ln="21      ">Working on our racial heart,
</l><l ln="22      ">Till it beams, in form sublime,
</l><l ln="23      ">Like a precious stone, which art
</l><l ln="24      ">Aided nature to adorn.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="25      ">Onward, upward, high and higher,
</l><l ln="26      ">&indent;Seeking each and all the light;
</l><l ln="27      ">Press, ye legions, on and up to
</l><l ln="28      ">&indent;Freedom's dazzling goal of light.
</l><l ln="29      ">Grant us peace, O gracious Master,
</l><l ln="30      ">Since our cause is one divine,
</l><l ln="31      ">Never let thou fell disaster
</l><l ln="32      ">Mark our star of Fate's decline!</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>
<pb n="75">
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200265034</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Beadle, Samuel Alfred<sombiog>232</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead>BABY DARLING.</mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200265034</ID><A1>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</A1><T1>BABY DARLING.</T1><PBL>W. A. Scott</PBL><Y1>1912</Y1><T2>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</attpoet><attidref>C2040198</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>C2040198</attidref><attdbase>African-American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>BABY DARLING.</mainhead><volhead>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1912</attpubn1><attpubn2>1912</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>232</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">Once</hi> a wee bit baby darling,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Pure as beauty, sweet as grace,
</l><l ln="3        ">Sat upon my knee and thrilled me
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;With her rare bewitching face;
</l><l ln="5        ">Face so fair, so charmed, so pregnant
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;With the glow of buoyant soul,
</l><l ln="7        ">That the angels paid her homage;
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;And, disputing earth's control,
</l><l ln="9        ">Trooped about her crib and worshipped
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;Baby darling's virgin soul.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="11      ">Lingered there and learned to love her,
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;And to envy us the child,
</l><l ln="13      ">Till our jealousies grew frenzied,
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;As the spirit world beguiled,
</l><l ln="15      ">Lured and charmed, and so enrapt her
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;With the ditties of the skies,
</l><l ln="17      ">That she pined and looked the languor,
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;Through her fever&hyphen;stricken eyes.
</l><l ln="19      ">All our mortal love we gave her,
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;But the angels:&mdash;paradise.</l></stanza>
<pb n="76">
<stanza><l ln="21      ">Yes, they took her, jealous angels,
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;Thus to take the baby child,
</l><l ln="23      ">All because she was the fairest
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;That e'er looked on them and smiled.
</l><l ln="25      ">Up in glory where they keep her,
</l><l ln="26      ">&indent;Can they, will they really be
</l><l ln="27      ">Half as careful, half as anxious
</l><l ln="28      ">&indent;Of our baby's weal as we?
</l><l ln="29      ">Did they really give her fever,
</l><l ln="30      ">&indent;In their joyous ecstacy?</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="31      ">Sick of pain, she daily wilted
</l><l ln="32      ">&indent;Through a typhus fever's blight,
</l><l ln="33      ">Till her spirit dropped its body&mdash;
</l><l ln="34      ">&indent;Far from earthly things took flight,
</l><l ln="35      ">With the cherubim then journeyed,
</l><l ln="36      ">&indent;Up in yon ethereal dome,
</l><l ln="37      ">Purest, fairest being, truly,
</l><l ln="38      ">&indent;That e'er through it flitted home
</l><l ln="39      ">To Elysian fields of glory,
</l><l ln="40      ">&indent;Where the Savior bids all come.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>
<pb n="79">
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200265035</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Beadle, Samuel Alfred<sombiog>232</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead>MY REMINGTON.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200265035</ID><A1>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</A1><T1>MY REMINGTON.</T1><PBL>W. A. Scott</PBL><Y1>1912</Y1><T2>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</attpoet><attidref>C2040199</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>C2040199</attidref><attdbase>African-American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>MY REMINGTON.</mainhead><volhead>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1912</attpubn1><attpubn2>1912</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>232</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">In</hi> the still and silent night,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">When I sit me down to write,
</l><l ln="3        ">There is mystery and ease,
</l><l ln="4        ">In the movement of the keys,
</l><l ln="5        ">And the smooth and even run
</l><l ln="6        ">Of my magic Remington.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="7        ">Let the man who glories still.
</l><l ln="8        ">In the ancient pen or quill,
</l><l ln="9        ">Take it of all glory shorn,
</l><l ln="10      ">Like that of his old ink horn;
</l><l ln="11      ">Put his paste&hyphen;brush in the ink
</l><l ln="12      ">When, if ever, he should think.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="13      ">I have now a wizard's wand,
</l><l ln="14      ">Underneath my dexter hand,
</l><l ln="15      ">Bringing happiness to me,
</l><l ln="16      ">Through its runic melody,
</l><l ln="17      ">Making time without the waste
</l><l ln="18      ">Of the ink quill in the paste.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>
<pb n="83">
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200265036</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Beadle, Samuel Alfred<sombiog>232</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead>ALICE.</mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200265036</ID><A1>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</A1><T1>ALICE.</T1><PBL>W. A. Scott</PBL><Y1>1912</Y1><T2>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</attpoet><attidref>C2040200</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>C2040200</attidref><attdbase>African-American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>ALICE.</mainhead><volhead>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1912</attpubn1><attpubn2>1912</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>232</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">Tomorrow</hi> 's but a dream, dear Alice,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;In truth, it never appears;
</l><l ln="3        ">The past, a tenantless old palace,
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;Where hope lies tombed in tears;
</l><l ln="5        ">The urn is broken, Alice,
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;Whence incense rose above;
</l><l ln="7        ">But you may see, if you will, today,
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;The magical haunts of love.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="9        ">My fancy sees a chalice,
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;A harp all strung, attuned,
</l><l ln="11      ">A famed, enchanted palace,
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;Where Cupid oft communed;
</l><l ln="13      ">The theme of his dreaming, Alice,
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;In waking or sleeping the same,
</l><l ln="15      ">A glory that ever dazzles,
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;Till it sets the soul a&hyphen;flame.</l></stanza>
<pb n="84">
<stanza><l ln="17      ">Like the burning bush on Horeb,
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;Or lit phosphoric seas,
</l><l ln="19      ">The dream is metamorphosed,
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;And Cupid makes wild pleas,
</l><l ln="21      ">For a glance of your dark eyes, Alice,
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;And a touch of your lips, my dear,
</l><l ln="23      ">For all the bliss of caressing,
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;Laughter, and song, and cheer.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="25      ">'Tis to you and none other, Alice,
</l><l ln="26      ">&indent;My thought reverts in its flight,
</l><l ln="27      ">A little perhaps out of ballas',
</l><l ln="28      ">&indent;Perhaps with too much delight;
</l><l ln="29      ">So crude, so humble and callous
</l><l ln="30      ">&indent;That a message it scarce can bear,
</l><l ln="31      ">From a heart that wears your image,
</l><l ln="32      ">&indent;And the passion that fixed it there.</l></stanza>
<pb n="85">
<stanza><l ln="33      ">Come thou with me, dear Alice,
</l><l ln="34      ">&indent;To where there's building for thee
</l><l ln="35      ">A loved, charmed, magical palace,
</l><l ln="36      ">&indent;Hard by the Mexic sea;
</l><l ln="37      ">Where date, and spice and lemon
</l><l ln="38      ">&indent;Doth blow perpetually,
</l><l ln="39      ">By that enchanted palace
</l><l ln="40      ">&indent;That looks out over the sea.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="41      ">Tomorrow? That's cruel, Alice,
</l><l ln="42      ">&indent;Why speak of a day that is not?
</l><l ln="43      ">That spoils the bliss of living,
</l><l ln="44      ">&indent;Makes mine a miserable lot,
</l><l ln="45      ">And love's enchanted palace
</l><l ln="46      ">&indent;A wild and desolate place;
</l><l ln="47      ">No land of dates and flowers
</l><l ln="48      ">&indent;Wert blessed without thy grace.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>
<pb n="87">
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200265037</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Beadle, Samuel Alfred<sombiog>232</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead>HILAND&hyphen;BUCKINGHAM.</mainhead> <attbytes>5Kb</attbytes><volhead>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200265037</ID><A1>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</A1><T1>HILAND&hyphen;BUCKINGHAM.</T1><PBL>W. A. Scott</PBL><Y1>1912</Y1><T2>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</attpoet><attidref>C2040201</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>C2040201</attidref><attdbase>African-American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>HILAND&hyphen;BUCKINGHAM.</mainhead><volhead>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>5Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1912</attpubn1><attpubn2>1912</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>232</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>
<edit>[Footnote: <bytes>1Kb</bytes>]</edit><note idref="CN010945">The following piece was intended as a brief satire on the
manner of conducting elections in the benevolent societies in the
State of Mississippi. That the manner of conducting elections
in many of these societies is corrupt, no one who regards truth
will deny:</note>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">Oh</hi>! have you heard the boastful song
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Of Highland&hyphen;Buckingham;
</l><l ln="3        ">Who often in their zeal go wrong,
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;And never care a damn.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="5        ">Gay, happy pals, the coin and bag,
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;The records and what not,
</l><l ln="7        ">They'd hold by fraud, or guile and gag,
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;While Eddie &ldquo;bulls&rdquo; the pot.</l></stanza>
<pb n="88">
<stanza><l ln="9        ">You hold the records and the seal,
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;And Buck 'll hold the bag,
</l><l ln="11      ">While John and Ed, by crooked deal,
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;The delegates will gag.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="13      ">The people's choice we may not be,
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;But what care we for that;
</l><l ln="15      ">We've fixed it so that you and &ldquo;me&rdquo;
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;And Johnny can stand pat.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="17      ">'Twas in the sunny month of May,
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;I think, or thereabout,
</l><l ln="19      ">When Eddie Jones devised a way,
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;Of counting people out.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="21      ">Since Eddie taught us how to buck
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;And gag the delegate,
</l><l ln="23      ">We'll slime the people's choice with muck
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;And let the rascals bleat.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="25      ">Our John will quack it like a duck,
</l><l ln="26      ">&indent;And straddle like a clown;
</l><l ln="27      ">Till 'twix vile roguery and luck
</l><l ln="28      ">&indent;We steal for him the crown.</l></stanza>
<pb n="89">
<stanza><l ln="29      ">For you the seal, for me the bag,
</l><l ln="30      ">&indent;Or you the bag and me
</l><l ln="31      ">The seal; we'll swap 'em as we wag,
</l><l ln="32      ">&indent;'Twix guile and tweedledee.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="33      ">We'll gull 'um here and gag 'um there;
</l><l ln="34      ">&indent;The delegates, you see,
</l><l ln="35      ">Have got no rights for which we care&mdash;
</l><l ln="36      ">&indent;Friend Buck, that's you and &ldquo;me.&rdquo;</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="37      ">You are my candidate, dear Buck,
</l><l ln="38      ">&indent;And I your jolly pal;
</l><l ln="39      ">You need not doubt your Hiland's pluck,
</l><l ln="40      ">&indent;It's cheek by jowl with mal.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="41      ">For me the seal, for you the bag,
</l><l ln="42      ">&indent;For John the gavel's trust;
</l><l ln="43      ">The people's choice we'll buck and gag,
</l><l ln="44      ">&indent;And take the bag or bust.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="45      ">'Tis true, we've been a little lax&mdash;
</l><l ln="46      ">&indent;Just twenty thousand short&mdash;
</l><l ln="47      ">But still we have the gall to tax
</l><l ln="48      ">&indent;The people while they snort.</l></stanza>
<pb n="90">
<stanza><l ln="49      ">They are such queer, such simple things;
</l><l ln="50      ">&indent;I mean the people, Buck;
</l><l ln="51      ">They'd leave their rights to clicks and rings
</l><l ln="52      ">&indent;And court the Boss and luck.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="53      ">The Boss, by jingo, he is a bird,
</l><l ln="54      ">&indent;There's magic in his name,
</l><l ln="55      ">Not by our suffrage; but his word
</l><l ln="56      ">&indent;We win or lose the game.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="57      ">On rights, the people would not toss
</l><l ln="58      ">&indent;A copper's head nor tail,
</l><l ln="59      ">They'd rather, far, to know the &ldquo;Boss&rdquo;
</l><l ln="60      ">&indent;Had drove a heeler's sale.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="61      ">The days of patriots have passed,
</l><l ln="62      ">&indent;Their principles are dead,
</l><l ln="63      ">The heeler has the sage outclassed
</l><l ln="64      ">&indent;And sports a price per head.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="65      ">For principles men used to fight,
</l><l ln="66      ">&indent;To 'venge a wrong would die,
</l><l ln="67      ">But now they slip a cog that's tight
</l><l ln="68      ">&indent;And barter rights for rye.</l></stanza>
<pb n="91">
<stanza><l ln="69      ">And there's a trait that's glorious,
</l><l ln="70      ">&indent;In diplomatic art,
</l><l ln="71      ">'Tis making right so odious
</l><l ln="72      ">&indent;That wrong seems &ldquo;pure of heart.&rdquo;</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>
<pb n="95">
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200265038</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Beadle, Samuel Alfred<sombiog>232</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead>MY BROTHER JOHN.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200265038</ID><A1>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</A1><T1>MY BROTHER JOHN.</T1><PBL>W. A. Scott</PBL><Y1>1912</Y1><T2>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</attpoet><attidref>C2040202</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>C2040202</attidref><attdbase>African-American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>MY BROTHER JOHN.</mainhead><volhead>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1912</attpubn1><attpubn2>1912</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>232</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">My</hi> brother John has beds of down
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">And mansions of his own;
</l><l ln="3        ">The humble bed where I rest my head
</l><l ln="4        ">Is little less than stone;
</l><l ln="5        ">But peace is there to soothe my care
</l><l ln="6        ">While Brother John has pride;
</l><l ln="7        ">So I pity John and all who bear
</l><l ln="8        ">Great fortune's weight and care.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="9        ">My brother John has fertile farms
</l><l ln="10      ">Of cotton, and corn and maize;
</l><l ln="11      ">While naught have I but earth and sky
</l><l ln="12      ">To look on all my days;
</l><l ln="13      ">Mine's not the lot to own the spot
</l><l ln="14      ">Of humble cabin home;
</l><l ln="15      ">And ne'er the wing of airy fame
</l><l ln="16      ">Buzzes about my name.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="17      ">My brother's hold is fixed on gold
</l><l ln="18      ">And auto cars for tour,
</l><l ln="19      ">That flash today in their gala way
</l><l ln="20      ">With rush and dash by the poor;
</l><l ln="21      ">When go I must, I tramp the dust
</l><l ln="22      ">Whither my brother speeds,
</l><l ln="23      ">Unawares to the common lot
</l><l ln="24      ">Of peer, and sage, and sot.</l></stanza>
<pb n="96">
<stanza><l ln="25      ">Brother John has a splendid lawn,
</l><l ln="26      ">Scythed and rolled and green,
</l><l ln="27      ">A verdant spot where such a sot
</l><l ln="28      ">As I am never seen.
</l><l ln="29      ">To all that plod, &ldquo;Keep off the sod,&rdquo;
</l><l ln="30      ">Is John's command today;
</l><l ln="31      ">And I pass on and muse why clay,
</l><l ln="32      ">Like mine, not John's, is gay.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>
<pb n="99">
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200265039</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Beadle, Samuel Alfred<sombiog>232</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead>KISS ME AGAIN.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200265039</ID><A1>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</A1><T1>KISS ME AGAIN.</T1><PBL>W. A. Scott</PBL><Y1>1912</Y1><T2>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</attpoet><attidref>C2040203</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>C2040203</attidref><attdbase>African-American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>KISS ME AGAIN.</mainhead><volhead>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1912</attpubn1><attpubn2>1912</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>232</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">&indent;<hi r="smcap">Oh</hi>, give me a kiss
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;To mate with the bliss
</l><l ln="3        ">Of the heart I swear, love, is thine;
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;Let beam a smile
</l><l ln="5        ">&indent;To cheer the while
</l><l ln="6        ">I give thee of all that is mine.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="7        ">&indent;Now, ere we part,
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;Let's feel your heart
</l><l ln="9        ">In unison beat, love, with mine;
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;Your head at rest,
</l><l ln="11      ">&indent;Sweet on my breast,
</l><l ln="12      ">While my arms, dear, about thee I twine.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="13      ">&indent;Kiss me again,
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;And then again!
</l><l ln="15      ">Turn Cupid wild tonight, sweetheart.
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;Thy soul and mine
</l><l ln="17      ">&indent;By a kiss confine,
</l><l ln="18      ">To love's wild dream, dear, ere we part.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>
<pb n="101">
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200265040</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Beadle, Samuel Alfred<sombiog>232</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead>MY DELIGHT.</mainhead> <attbytes>4Kb</attbytes><volhead>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200265040</ID><A1>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</A1><T1>MY DELIGHT.</T1><PBL>W. A. Scott</PBL><Y1>1912</Y1><T2>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</attpoet><attidref>C2040204</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>C2040204</attidref><attdbase>African-American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>MY DELIGHT.</mainhead><volhead>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>4Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1912</attpubn1><attpubn2>1912</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>232</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>
<edit>[Footnote: <bytes>1Kb</bytes>]</edit><note idref="CN010946"><p>About two miles, as the crow flies, south from Meridian, in
Lauderdale County, Mississippi, stands Mt. Barton, probably the
highest hill in East Mississippi. One can get a splendid view
of the surrounding country from this hill; and, in the early morning
or late afternoon, the beauty of the landscape viewed from
its summit is pleasing.</p>
<p>I frequently visit Mt. Barton, which I call the Heights of
Lauderdale. I can see and contemplate Meridian better from
this point, and the sweet sensations which come when the winds
play among the pines, and the absence of the din and noise of
the city, make it a happy resort for a weary mind.</p></note>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">I can</hi> but feel a swell of soul,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Over my vision's broader scope,
</l><l ln="3        ">When from the city's mart I stroll
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;And climb along the northern slope,
</l><l ln="5        ">&indent;&indent;Of the Heights of Lauderdale.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="6        ">Hard by, a heath of Lauderdale,
</l><l ln="7        ">&indent;A verdant sweep of broken lea,
</l><l ln="8        ">Rolls into knolls from out the vale,
</l><l ln="9        ">&indent;And undulates and swells a sea
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;&indent;Of billowy emerald waves.</l></stanza>
<pb n="102">
<stanza><l ln="11      ">Far off on that sea there lies,
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;North of the Heights of Lauderdale,
</l><l ln="13      ">Meridian, 'neath a haze of skies,
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;And seems, upon that distant vale,
</l><l ln="15      ">&indent;&indent;Fleet like, anchored on the deep.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="16      ">How often have I lingered there,
</l><l ln="17      ">&indent;To have my simple thought dome teem,
</l><l ln="18      ">With fancy's fictions of the fair,
</l><l ln="19      ">&indent;And catch a glimpse of beauty beam,
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;&indent;Scintillate and dazzle there.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="21      ">And when beneath some lofty pine,
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;I muse on Nature's loveliness,
</l><l ln="23      ">As oft it seems something divine,
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;Places a rare peculiar stress,
</l><l ln="25      ">&indent;&indent;Of melody in the pines.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="26      ">Among the pines of Lauderdale,
</l><l ln="27      ">&indent;A whispered cadence sighs along,
</l><l ln="28      ">And when the winds become a gale,
</l><l ln="29      ">&indent;The verdant hills burst into song
</l><l ln="30      ">&indent;&indent;And sweetly soughs ravien.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="31      ">And far away down the cultured vale,
</l><l ln="32      ">&indent;Echoing goes the evening hymn,
</l><l ln="33      ">Of some rude swain of Lauderdale;
</l><l ln="34      ">&indent;Soothing and sweet, the lay of him
</l><l ln="35      ">&indent;&indent;Chimes with the metre wild.</l></stanza>
<pb n="103">
<stanza><l ln="36      ">The metre wild, the metre wild,
</l><l ln="37      ">&indent;How many an eve I loiter where,
</l><l ln="38      ">By its sweet melody beguiled,
</l><l ln="39      ">&indent;I muse on nature's charms and share
</l><l ln="40      ">&indent;&indent;Her metrical symposium.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="41      ">Sublime the scene when twilight flies,
</l><l ln="42      ">&indent;Up through the green tines of the pines,
</l><l ln="43      ">As, on the deep vermillion skies,
</l><l ln="44      ">&indent;Day, weary and worn, declines,
</l><l ln="45      ">&indent;&indent;Beaming last on Lauderdale.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="46      ">There, looking on him spent, supine,
</l><l ln="47      ">&indent;How oft have I been filled with awe,
</l><l ln="48      ">To see his gold on emerald shine,
</l><l ln="49      ">&indent;And crimson fingered evening draw
</l><l ln="50      ">&indent;&indent;The starry curtains of the night.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="51      ">Again to hear the wild anthem,
</l><l ln="52      ">&indent;The intonations of the pines,
</l><l ln="53      ">And all the mystic airs of them
</l><l ln="54      ">&indent;A&hyphen;soughing through the vast confines
</l><l ln="55      ">&indent;&indent;Of Lauderdale is my delight.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>
<pb n="105">
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200265041</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Beadle, Samuel Alfred<sombiog>232</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead>NICKNAMES.</mainhead> <attbytes>5Kb</attbytes><volhead>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200265041</ID><A1>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</A1><T1>NICKNAMES.</T1><PBL>W. A. Scott</PBL><Y1>1912</Y1><T2>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</attpoet><attidref>C2040205</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>C2040205</attidref><attdbase>African-American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>NICKNAMES.</mainhead><volhead>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>5Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1912</attpubn1><attpubn2>1912</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>232</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">De</hi> sunny years am gone and all
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;De jolly makin' gloree time,
</l><l ln="3        ">From farm an' hut an' manshun hall
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;De cullurd population's gwine,
</l><l ln="5        ">&indent;&indent;Tur try de styles uv city folks.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="6        ">De Boss he lef' some time ergo,
</l><l ln="7        ">&indent;And built er house in town, yer kno',
</l><l ln="8        ">His plans dey seem ter thrive, an' so
</l><l ln="9        ">&indent;De cullurd brother thinks he'll go
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;&indent;An' just metroperlate er while.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="11      ">An' when he gits ter town, yer kno',
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;He's ruint by de fashuns there;
</l><l ln="13      ">'Tis &ldquo;Miss and Madum&rdquo; So and So;
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;'Tis Mr. Johnson or 'tis &ldquo;Square&rdquo;;
</l><l ln="15      ">&indent;&indent;Dhey all has nicknames up in town.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="16      ">Dhar's Sam, what quit his plowin' biz
</l><l ln="17      ">&indent;Ter move to town dis very year;
</l><l ln="18      ">Well, he's stark crazy, 'deed he is;
</l><l ln="19      ">&indent;Jist call 'im Sam, an' you'll hear
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;&indent;Him 'rectin' yer, &ldquo;Dis 'm Mr. Jones.&rdquo;</l></stanza>
<pb n="106">
<stanza><l ln="21      ">Lizer, his wife, done ruint too,
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;Wid her 'tis &ldquo;Madum, ef yer please,&rdquo;
</l><l ln="23      ">An' den she'll highfalute wid you
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;Behint her fan, wid all de ease
</l><l ln="25      ">&indent;&indent;De big folks does up dhar in town.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="26      ">Sure! ebry blessed one uv dem
</l><l ln="27      ">&indent;Done changed his name, an' dat aint all;
</l><l ln="28      ">Dhey dress so fine, both gals and men,
</l><l ln="29      ">&indent;Er country mam looks ruther small
</l><l ln="30      ">&indent;&indent;Besides of dem when she's in town.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="31      ">Dhey's got er new fandangle word
</l><l ln="32      ">&indent;For our ol' fashun names, somehow,
</l><l ln="33      ">Dhey titles use, us neber heard
</l><l ln="34      ">&indent;Before&mdash;de elder's doctor now,
</l><l ln="35      ">&indent;&indent;An' de church benches all am pews.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="36      ">Chile, what yer thinks dhey calls de lane
</l><l ln="37      ">&indent;Dat trails er long betwix de stores?
</l><l ln="38      ">Nawp, 'taint &ldquo;Big road,&rdquo; yer gess is vain
</l><l ln="39      ">&indent;Yer'll crack dat woolly pate uv yours
</l><l ln="40      ">&indent;&indent;'Fore yer ken gess what is er lane.</l></stanza>
<pb n="107">
<stanza><l ln="41      ">&ldquo;Cross&hyphen;road?&rdquo; No, sir ree, try er gin;
</l><l ln="42      ">&indent;Nawp, 'tis nuthin' like er highways
</l><l ln="43      ">Nuther! I don't care whar yer's bin
</l><l ln="44      ">&indent;Nur what yer's heard in all yer days,
</l><l ln="45      ">&indent;&indent;'Twas nuthin' like &ldquo;Bully&hyphen;Yard&rdquo; fur lane.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="46      ">Yer ought ter see um struttin' down
</l><l ln="47      ">&indent;Dat &ldquo;Bully&hyphen;Yard.&rdquo; It tickles me
</l><l ln="48      ">Ter see dem niggers up in town;
</l><l ln="49      ">&indent;See Lawyer Bhoon wid Dr. Lee,
</l><l ln="50      ">&indent;&indent;An' hear dem gent'mens 'scussin news.</l></stanza>
<pb n="109">
<stanza><l ln="51      ">Yer'd think dat some great folks done come
</l><l ln="52      ">&indent;Like Linctom, Grant and Douglas wuz,
</l><l ln="53      ">Er 'batin' human ri'ts upon
</l><l ln="54      ">&indent;De public square in Dixie, c'uz
</l><l ln="55      ">&indent;&indent;Et kinder 'pears dat way to me.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="56      ">'Taint nuthin' like et uster be,
</l><l ln="57      ">&indent;Wid ax, an' hoe, an' plow; dat's changed;
</l><l ln="58      ">Dar's Bishop Smith wid his D. D.,
</l><l ln="59      ">&indent;Presidin' Elder Reveren' Grange,
</l><l ln="60      ">&indent;&indent;An' Madum Sloan, what leas'd de quare.</l></stanza>
<pb n="110">
<stanza><l ln="61      ">De rag dat's on de bush am dheirs;
</l><l ln="62      ">&indent;Ruther, dey take de bush an' all
</l><l ln="63      ">When 't comes to highfalutin' airs,
</l><l ln="64      ">&indent;An' showin' off; ez I recall,
</l><l ln="65      ">&indent;&indent;Dhar's nuffin' real 'bout none uv dem.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="66      ">Uv course, dhar is a better folk,
</l><l ln="67      ">&indent;What's prudent, wise and good; but these
</l><l ln="68      ">Mus' serve an' wear de gallin' yoke,
</l><l ln="69      ">&indent;An' be de prey uv make&hyphen;believes,
</l><l ln="70      ">&indent;&indent;An' low an' worthless renurgades.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="71      ">Who'd have yer b'leave dhey had not seed
</l><l ln="72      ">&indent;Er mule, or cotton patch, or ax;
</l><l ln="73      ">An' claim to be so wise, indeed,
</l><l ln="74      ">&indent;Et somehow all yer senses tax,
</l><l ln="75      ">&indent;&indent;Ter 'zacley 'scribe um as dhey is.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>
<pb n="113">
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200265042</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Beadle, Samuel Alfred<sombiog>232</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead>THE SOVEREIGN.</mainhead> <attbytes>5Kb</attbytes><volhead>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200265042</ID><A1>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</A1><T1>THE SOVEREIGN.</T1><PBL>W. A. Scott</PBL><Y1>1912</Y1><T2>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</attpoet><attidref>C2040206</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>C2040206</attidref><attdbase>African-American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>THE SOVEREIGN.</mainhead><volhead>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>5Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1912</attpubn1><attpubn2>1912</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>232</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">We</hi> have a mighty government of high and brilliant fame,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Triumphant we the suffrage wield and all our kith and kin;
</l><l ln="3        ">And those who would the nation rule by equity, not awe,
</l><l ln="4        ">Know the President is ruler only in the people's name;
</l><l ln="5        ">For the sovereign is the people, and the people's will is law.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="6        ">The voter he is royalized, his dame's a sovereign's queen,
</l><l ln="7        ">The millions of them common heirs apparent to a throne,
</l><l ln="8        ">Whose prowess is invincible, whose glory is supreme;
</l><l ln="9        ">And whom they will they designate to wield the mace, I wean.
</l><l ln="10      ">Their common heritage, the mace, rotation its regime.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="11      ">And Washington, impregnable, did Freedom's glory set
</l><l ln="12      ">Above the rage of passion and beyond ambition's blow;
</l><l ln="13      ">And Lincoln died to keep it there, the honor of the West;
</l><l ln="14      ">A government of commoners, that is triumphant yet
</l><l ln="15      ">In the suffrage of the people, for the people's reign is best.</l></stanza>
<pb n="114">
<stanza><l ln="16      ">Yet Roosevelt brought us princely whims, and honor and renown;
</l><l ln="17      ">And led the Russ and Japanese to pleasant fields to peace.
</l><l ln="18      ">And sent our valiant fighting tars a spinning round the globe,
</l><l ln="19      ">And boosted up the Cabinet, and held the Congress down,
</l><l ln="20      ">And kept the trust contending with the governmental probe.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="21      ">A brilliant man of letters, he eclipsed the fourth estate,
</l><l ln="22      ">And kept the galleys flooded with his seas of manuscript,
</l><l ln="23      ">So coached our representatives, with messages of whim,
</l><l ln="24      ">The great became his echoist, &ldquo;My policies to prate,&rdquo;
</l><l ln="25      ">And everything spectacular was left to fate and him.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="26      ">He found among our nation's hoards but one who tells the truth,
</l><l ln="27      ">And he is wasting dictums on the Ananias clubs,
</l><l ln="28      ">And holds in his opinion, and by all the rules of law,
</l><l ln="29      ">Apparent is presumption and self&hyphen;evident is proof,
</l><l ln="30      ">That Harriman, and Tillman, and the World once made a draw.</l></stanza>
<pb n="115">
<stanza><l ln="31      ">All glory to the President, for truly he has rights
</l><l ln="32      ">Which weaker mortals haven't got and wise ones wouldn't have,
</l><l ln="33      ">For he can wield a mammoth club and wear his cap awry;
</l><l ln="34      ">With fiction's greatness he can come, crazed by his frantic frights,
</l><l ln="35      ">And frail the mischief out of many such as you and I.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="36      ">Ay, truly is the President sagacious, great and wise,
</l><l ln="37      ">Who keeps his soul in peace and reigns o'er eighty million kings
</l><l ln="38      ">Who are themselves the common heirs and lords who emulate
</l><l ln="39      ">The virtues of our patron sires who did to us devise
</l><l ln="40      ">The tenue of the suffrage and the legacy of state.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="41      ">The President is glorious, we think he is sublime,
</l><l ln="42      ">Whene'er he represents the will of eighty million souls;
</l><l ln="43      ">A commoner of commoners, by commoners enthroned,
</l><l ln="44      ">And made the peer of all the kings of every age and clime,
</l><l ln="45      ">Whose glory none will dare despoil, and none has yet disowned.</l></stanza>
<pb n="116">
<stanza><l ln="46      ">The patriots who built the realm, have in their will decreed,
</l><l ln="47      ">The sceptre is the people's and among them shall rotate,
</l><l ln="48      ">Till home rule is immortalized in ev'ry people's reign;
</l><l ln="49      ">For royal blood's a fiction and all royalty's a creed,
</l><l ln="50      ">And suffrage of the people still the hope of state and fane.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="51      ">So here's to Mister President, and here's to Taft the man,
</l><l ln="52      ">A commoner of commoners by commoners enthroned;
</l><l ln="53      ">And here is to the commoners, my countrymen, my peers,
</l><l ln="54      ">And here's to law and equity, to party and to clan,
</l><l ln="55      ">And here's to equal suffrage in our government's careers.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="56      ">God bless our common country, and preserve chief of state,
</l><l ln="57      ">And solace him who has the charge, with all Thy gracious love;
</l><l ln="58      ">Lest many should, perchance, forget this is the people's reign,
</l><l ln="59      ">We pray Thee, Lord, to keep it so the sceptre shall rotate,
</l><l ln="60      ">The common people e'er among in commonwealth and fane.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>
<pb n="119">
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200265043</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Beadle, Samuel Alfred<sombiog>232</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead>SLEEPY CORNER.</mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200265043</ID><A1>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</A1><T1>SLEEPY CORNER.</T1><PBL>W. A. Scott</PBL><Y1>1912</Y1><T2>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</attpoet><attidref>C2040207</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>C2040207</attidref><attdbase>African-American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>SLEEPY CORNER.</mainhead><volhead>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1912</attpubn1><attpubn2>1912</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>232</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">Sam</hi>, the Garbager, had carpet,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;And some scraps of office jot,
</l><l ln="3        ">Optomacy stooped to throw him,
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;As he passed from lot to lot,
</l><l ln="5        ">And with these he decked his cabin
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;In a rather modern style;
</l><l ln="7        ">But himself remained old&hyphen;fashioned
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;Like&mdash;simple and true the while.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="9        ">And the milk of human kindness
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;Seemed to bubble from his heart,
</l><l ln="11      ">As he rolled about the city
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;In his two&hyphen;wheeled garbage cart.
</l><l ln="13      ">He could tell about the weather
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;From the corns upon his feet,
</l><l ln="15      ">And he said, &ldquo;De kind dat rests yer
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;Is de drizzle, rain or sleet.&rdquo;</l></stanza>
<pb n="120">
<stanza><l ln="17      ">Dhar am sometin in de wedder,
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;Dat yer can't jist al'ays splain,
</l><l ln="19      ">When the clouds am runnin' rivers
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;In de drizzlin' of de rain;
</l><l ln="21      ">Ween de win' am jist ez quiet,
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;Ez de las' yer's mouldin' leaves
</l><l ln="23      ">Wid nothin' breaking silence
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;'Cep'en murmurs on your eves.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="25      ">Wid de night ez dark ez Hades,
</l><l ln="26      ">&indent;An' er tinyus po'in rain,
</l><l ln="27      ">Er ripplin' into murmurs
</l><l ln="28      ">&indent;Off yer windo' sill an' pane,
</l><l ln="29      ">Dhar am som'thin' in de weder
</l><l ln="30      ">&indent;Lak er op'ate so it seems
</l><l ln="31      ">Dat brings yer deeper slumber,
</l><l ln="32      ">&indent;Dat wakes yer lighter dreams.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="33      ">In dear ol' sleepy corner,
</l><l ln="34      ">&indent;Whar 'lax'tion grows and grows,
</l><l ln="35      ">Tell yer nap and nod ter music,
</l><l ln="36      ">&indent;Dat's er lullin' yer to 'pose.
</l><l ln="37      ">An' de study ripplin' measure
</l><l ln="38      ">&indent;Dat am tumblin' off yer eves.
</l><l ln="39      ">Seems er lullaby of angels,
</l><l ln="40      ">&indent;Forcin' worries all ter leave.</l></stanza>
<pb n="121">
<stanza><l ln="41      ">Den yer soul all ober joyed
</l><l ln="42      ">&indent;Wid de dreams de driz'le weaves;
</l><l ln="43      ">Kinder feels dat et am courted
</l><l ln="44      ">&indent;By de nymps of reveries;
</l><l ln="45      ">An' yer mouth er fallin' open,
</l><l ln="46      ">&indent;Hangs yer chin erpun yer chest,
</l><l ln="47      ">While yer soul goes 'splorin' dream lan'
</l><l ln="48      ">&indent;Ez de driz'le lulls ter rest.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>
<pb n="124">
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200265044</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Beadle, Samuel Alfred<sombiog>232</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead>FOR A WOMAN.</mainhead> <attbytes>5Kb</attbytes><volhead>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200265044</ID><A1>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</A1><T1>FOR A WOMAN.</T1><PBL>W. A. Scott</PBL><Y1>1912</Y1><T2>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</attpoet><attidref>C2040208</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>C2040208</attidref><attdbase>African-American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>FOR A WOMAN.</mainhead><volhead>Lyrics of the Under World (1912)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>5Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1912</attpubn1><attpubn2>1912</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>232</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">Eden</hi>, lost to all but fancy,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Was it ever aught but legend
</l><l ln="3        ">Handed down from sire to son,
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;As descriptive of the region,
</l><l ln="5        ">Of the sunny haunts of love?
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;Famous garden where the passion,
</l><l ln="7        ">Bursting first disclosed the morn
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;Whose effulgent, beaming glory
</l><l ln="9        ">Cleft old Chaos, brain and spine;
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;Lit up incense burning shrine,
</l><l ln="11      ">In the heart of man for Eve.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="12      ">'Round that shrine the zeal of Adam,
</l><l ln="13      ">&indent;Glowing like the flaming sword,
</l><l ln="14      ">Soon forgot his peaceful Eden,
</l><l ln="15      ">&indent;And the order of his lord;
</l><l ln="16      ">Left the garden to its thistles,
</l><l ln="17      ">&indent;And his Master to His wrath,
</l><l ln="18      ">Bartered Eden for a woman,
</l><l ln="19      ">&indent;Braved the fates to please his wife;
</l><l ln="20      ">Took her from the lap of nature
</l><l ln="21      ">&indent;Just as God had fashioned her,
</l><l ln="22      ">In her rare bewitchery.</l></stanza>
<pb n="125">
<stanza><l ln="23      ">Ever since that fatal error,
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;Whether fact or mythic story,
</l><l ln="25      ">From the ancient tomes of thought,
</l><l ln="26      ">&indent;Brought by art through mystic glory,
</l><l ln="27      ">They have journeyed, both astray,
</l><l ln="28      ">&indent;Over many steeps of woe;
</l><l ln="29      ">Through the fens and bogs of shame,
</l><l ln="30      ">&indent;Fled from sorrow unto sorrow,
</l><l ln="31      ">Sounding all the deeps of pain;
</l><l ln="32      ">&indent;But never crossed, nor can again,
</l><l ln="33      ">Eden in their pilgrimage.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="34      ">Talked with God in burning bushes,
</l><l ln="35      ">&indent;Held the seas till Isr'el passed;
</l><l ln="36      ">Ate of manna fresh from heaven;
</l><l ln="37      ">&indent;Took a town with trumpet blast;
</l><l ln="38      ">Slept with lions, stood in fire;
</l><l ln="39      ">&indent;And, in Prince of Bethlehem,
</l><l ln="40      ">Had a God to mourn their dead,
</l><l ln="41      ">&indent;And vivify the corpse again;
</l><l ln="42      ">But ne'er since man squandered Eden
</l><l ln="43      ">&indent;On the fancy of a maiden,
</l><l ln="44      ">Has he found the land of bliss.</l></stanza>
<pb n="126">
<stanza><l ln="45      ">May be, after all, old Eden
</l><l ln="46      ">&indent;Is wrapped within our meaner selves
</l><l ln="47      ">Hid beneath our pride ard envy;
</l><l ln="48      ">&indent;That the sword which us repels;
</l><l ln="49      ">Is our secret wickedness:
</l><l ln="50      ">&indent;Could we deftly lift the curtain
</l><l ln="51      ">Which the cunning serpent draws,
</l><l ln="52      ">&indent;Like the veil of night about us,
</l><l ln="53      ">We would find that paradise,
</l><l ln="54      ">&indent;Like a flower in winter, lies
</l><l ln="55      ">'Neath the stubbles of our souls,</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="56      ">&ldquo;So near and yet so far away&rdquo;,
</l><l ln="57      ">&indent;For who has ever purged his heart,
</l><l ln="58      ">Of all the guilt that in it lies,
</l><l ln="59      ">&indent;Though the purging would impart
</l><l ln="60      ">To him the bliss of paradise?
</l><l ln="61      ">&indent;Who does not harbor in his breast
</l><l ln="62      ">The fruitage of forbidden things
</l><l ln="63      ">&indent;Culled from beauty's lips and heart,
</l><l ln="64      ">And folded in between the leaves
</l><l ln="65      ">&indent;Of memory's roll of reveries:
</l><l ln="66      ">A charm, a hope, a dream!</l></stanza>
<pb n="127">
<stanza><l ln="67      ">Whether truth, fancy or legend
</l><l ln="68      ">&indent;Is what allures our faith through fears,
</l><l ln="69      ">Let us hope beyond the shadows
</l><l ln="70      ">&indent;Of this wilderness of tears,
</l><l ln="71      ">We shall reach the blest dominion
</l><l ln="72      ">&indent;That so long has failed us here;
</l><l ln="73      ">Where our friends will cease to doubt us,
</l><l ln="74      ">&indent;Where our foes will learn to love;
</l><l ln="75      ">Still let's hope to find the Eden
</l><l ln="76      ">&indent;Whence we wandered with our maiden;
</l><l ln="77      ">If not here, beyond the bourn.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="78      ">Let us hope life's pilgrimage,
</l><l ln="79      ">&indent;Has some other goal than Hell;
</l><l ln="80      ">Hope that we may find the glory,
</l><l ln="81      ">&indent;Whence the first degenerate fell;
</l><l ln="82      ">Hope to foil the shafts of envy;
</l><l ln="83      ">&indent;Hope to sooth the pangs of pain;
</l><l ln="84      ">Hope to find our dead are living;
</l><l ln="85      ">&indent;Hope to find our living dead
</l><l ln="86      ">To the errors time is weaving;
</l><l ln="87      ">&indent;To lip service and deceiving
</l><l ln="88      ">Hope to conquer death at last.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>
<pb n="129">
<div2>
