<newatts><attidref>C2040211</attidref><attdbase>African-American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>IMPROMPTU.</mainhead><volhead>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1899</attpubn1><attpubn2>1899</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>232</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">Many</hi> and many a year ago
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;I heard of those ancient rhymers,
</l><l ln="3        ">Those builders of our poetic lore,
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;The grand old vanished timers,
</l><l ln="5        ">Were always born and never made;
</l><l ln="6        ">That they by inspiration bade
</l><l ln="7        ">The eulogies and melodies
</l><l ln="8        ">From the spirit's emotions rise,
</l><l ln="9        ">Filling the earth, the air, the skies
</l><l ln="10      ">With beings from their paradise,
</l><l ln="11      ">&indent;Of esthetic thought and rapture.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="12      ">Then the muses chased the poets down
</l><l ln="13      ">&indent;From infancy to hoariness,
</l><l ln="14      ">With the genius' proffered crown
</l><l ln="15      ">&indent;And surprised them in their idleness
</l><l ln="16      ">With the coronation brilliancy
</l><l ln="17      ">Of sweet poetic ecstacy,
</l><l ln="18      ">When the metrical song moved along
</l><l ln="19      ">In melody's natural measure.
</l><l ln="20      ">A radient royal pleasure,
</l><l ln="21      ">Which the favored took at leisure
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;Without the minutest effort.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="23      ">That this is true I sometimes feel,
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;And write a feeble line or two,
</l><l ln="25      ">Whene'er the muses o'er me steal
</l><l ln="26      ">&indent;And I fain would strike the lyre too:
</l><l ln="27      ">But that &ldquo;always born, never made,&rdquo;
</l><l ln="28      ">From the fanciful flight have stayed,
</l><pb n="8">
<l ln="29      ">Brilliant spondee and sweet touchee,
</l><l ln="30      ">Awaiting the inspiring tole,
</l><l ln="31      ">To move the music of my soul
</l><l ln="32      ">To the cadence of the poet's role,
</l><l ln="33      ">&indent;Of proficiency without toil.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="34      ">No, Nature has no favored ones,
</l><l ln="35      ">&indent;All are what themselves would be;
</l><l ln="36      ">Through endless toil Ambition's sons
</l><l ln="37      ">&indent;Adorn themselves with victory:
</l><l ln="38      ">So I will write it, right or wrong,
</l><l ln="39      ">Everyone shall hear the song,
</l><l ln="40      ">I wish to sing of Evylin;
</l><l ln="41      ">The chaste and lovely Evylin,
</l><l ln="42      ">Tho' all the measure set therein
</l><l ln="43      ">Is not what it should have been,
</l><l ln="44      ">&indent;To make the Criticaster's poem.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>
<pb n="14">
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200265050</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Beadle, Samuel Alfred<sombiog>232</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead>MARY JANE'S BRIGHT EYE.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200265050</ID><A1>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</A1><T1>MARY JANE'S BRIGHT EYE.</T1><PBL>W. A. Scott</PBL><Y1>1912</Y1><T2>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</attpoet><attidref>C2040212</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>C2040212</attidref><attdbase>African-American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>MARY JANE'S BRIGHT EYE.</mainhead><volhead>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1899</attpubn1><attpubn2>1899</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>232</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">Oft</hi> in the hush of twilight,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;When the golden sunbeams die,
</l><l ln="3        ">There beams for me the light
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;Of Mary Jane's bright eye:
</l><l ln="5        ">&indent;&indent;As she swings,
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;&indent;And sings,
</l><l ln="7        ">And lingers late,
</l><l ln="8        ">For me at the cottage gate.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="9        ">Whenever the day goes wrong
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;With the weight of cruel cares,
</l><l ln="11      ">The lustre of her orbs
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;Beam brighter though in tears,
</l><l ln="13      ">&indent;&indent;As she weeps
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;&indent;And sweeps,
</l><l ln="15      ">And watches late
</l><l ln="16      ">My coming through the cottage gate.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="17      ">Oh! the eyes of my Mary Jane!
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;Dark and sparkling, lovely eyes,
</l><l ln="19      ">Where stood my reflected self
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;Mirrored in paradise,
</l><l ln="21      ">&indent;&indent;As she hung,
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;&indent;And swung,
</l><l ln="23      ">And lingered late,
</l><l ln="24      ">And kissed me o'er the cottage gate.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>
<pb n="15">
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200265051</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Beadle, Samuel Alfred<sombiog>232</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead>SONNETS TO MY LOVE.</mainhead> <attbytes>16Kb</attbytes><volhead>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200265051</ID><A1>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</A1><T1>SONNETS TO MY LOVE.</T1><PBL>W. A. Scott</PBL><Y1>1912</Y1><T2>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</attpoet><attidref>C2040213</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>C2040213</attidref><attdbase>African-American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>SONNETS TO MY LOVE.</mainhead><volhead>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>16Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1899</attpubn1><attpubn2>1899</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>232</attautid><litpack></litpack><attgenre>Sonnet</attgenre></newatts>
<stanza><caption>I</caption>
<firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">I stood</hi>, when life was full of buoyant hope,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;At sunrise, in the vanished years now flown,
</l><l ln="3        ">&indent;With my mother, on that piece of earth that's known
</l><l ln="4        ">To those who've had mother's affections ope
</l><l ln="5        ">The gate, and leave ajar, to their full scope,
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;The delightful ways of sweet childhood's home,
</l><l ln="7        ">&indent;And felt her hand of blessing on her own&mdash;
</l><l ln="8        ">And now when fancy calls up those remote
</l><l ln="9        ">Times, though its far too late, I appreciate
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;Her sole absorbing theme, maternal love;
</l><l ln="11      ">Alone on this, the greatest human trait,
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;God has written in the archives above
</l><l ln="13      ">Divine; but she left me disconsolate,
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;Alone in oblivion's sphere to move.</l></stanza>
<stanza><caption>II</caption>
<l ln="15      ">I turn away from this scene of sadness,
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;To embrace thee, fairest of all the earth,
</l><l ln="17      ">&indent;Thou thrillest me and all my friends with mirth
</l><l ln="18      ">And incitest hope that counsels cheerfulness,
</l><l ln="19      ">And bidst me to no longer doubt; nor guess
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;At the supremacy of thyself and worth,
</l><l ln="21      ">&indent;Nor longer to compare thee with the serf;
</l><l ln="22      ">Life's meaner beings and their littleness.
</l><l ln="23      ">Thou art celestial, fair sweetheart of mine,
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;Divinely fashioned in thine every part,
</l><l ln="25      ">The light that dazzles in those eyes of thine,
</l><pb n="16">
<l ln="26      ">&indent;Has won until now my unconquered heart;
</l><l ln="27      ">I kneel, divested of self, at love's shrine
</l><l ln="28      ">&indent;And offer thee all my confiding heart.</l></stanza>
<stanza><caption>III</caption>
<l ln="29      ">It is thine for good, for better, or for worse,
</l><l ln="30      ">&indent;Faithful to remain through all the year
</l><l ln="31      ">&indent;Of checkered life's bright sunshine, cloud and tear,
</l><l ln="32      ">Thine whatever be thy sad reverse,
</l><l ln="33      ">Thine till the collapse of the universe;
</l><l ln="34      ">&indent;Thine to revere, to love, adore, to wear
</l><l ln="35      ">&indent;Thine image on my soul; nor fate, nor fear,
</l><l ln="36      ">Weal nor woe, nor Mammon's power coerce
</l><l ln="37      ">Me into cold forgetfulness of thee,
</l><l ln="38      ">&indent;Because thou still livest alone for me
</l><l ln="39      ">And stern, cold, destructive adversity,
</l><l ln="40      ">&indent;Has left thee goddess of prosperity,
</l><l ln="41      ">To inspire me. Today, o'er life's grim sea,
</l><l ln="42      ">&indent;I hear the glad acclaim of victory.</l></stanza>
<stanza><caption>IV</caption>
<l ln="43      ">It's sweet to hear the milkmaid's rural song
</l><l ln="44      ">&indent;Floating in its melody on the wind;
</l><l ln="45      ">&indent;The buoyant echo of a tranquil mind;
</l><l ln="46      ">And sweeter still to see the waving corn,
</l><l ln="47      ">Falling beneath the scythe throughout the long
</l><l ln="48      ">&indent;Harvest days; and yet still more so to find
</l><l ln="49      ">&indent;The frugal meal spread by the angel kind,
</l><l ln="50      ">Which God gave to be our helpmate. The horn
</l><l ln="51      ">Of plenty thrives in her delicate hand,
</l><l ln="52      ">&indent;And economy fills our humble board.
</l><l ln="53      ">It is sweet as you tread a foreign strand,
</l><l ln="54      ">&indent;Where the ships from over the sea stand moored;
</l><pb n="17">
<l ln="55      ">To learn anew that in your native land,
</l><l ln="56      ">&indent;Confiding lovers your memories hoard.</l></stanza>
<stanza><caption>V</caption>
<l ln="57      ">It is sweet to have narrated at night
</l><l ln="58      ">&indent;The travels of him who has seen the earth,
</l><l ln="59      ">&indent;When hoary winter makes of all a dearth,
</l><l ln="60      ">And the fires of peace in our homes burn bright
</l><l ln="61      ">As we mix our wines and our friendships plight,
</l><l ln="62      ">&indent;O'er the bright nectar that kindles the mirth,
</l><l ln="63      ">&indent;Of the jolly souls that surround our hearth
</l><l ln="64      ">With their witty convivial delight.
</l><l ln="65      ">But sweeter, sweeter far, than all of these,
</l><l ln="66      ">&indent;Are the delicious joys young lovers steal,
</l><l ln="67      ">While making love beneath the verdant trees,
</l><l ln="68      ">&indent;As they feel the full, wild, passionate weal
</l><l ln="69      ">Of first love's grand emotions; when the breeze
</l><l ln="70      ">&indent;Of mutual hope fans the fire they feel.</l></stanza>
<stanza><caption>VI</caption>
<l ln="71      ">But this to me is the sweetest by night,
</l><l ln="72      ">&indent;With my love's soft voice as the complement,
</l><l ln="73      ">&indent;Chiming the cadence of its merriment,
</l><l ln="74      ">While her heart's at ease, and her spirit bright,
</l><l ln="75      ">Allures the soul in its ecstatic flight,
</l><l ln="76      ">&indent;To the fullest extent of its sentient,
</l><l ln="77      ">&indent;Passionately, bewildered sentiment,
</l><l ln="78      ">Of love's profound, affectionate delight.
</l><l ln="79      ">To feel the touch of this angelic one,
</l><l ln="80      ">&indent;In the sublime grace of her fellowship;
</l><l ln="81      ">Makes the heart beat quick and the spirit run,
</l><l ln="82      ">&indent;Pregnant with great bliss, into Cupid's ship
</l><l ln="83      ">O'er oceans of doubt, to love's dominion,
</l><l ln="84      ">&indent;As on her upturned face I press my lip.</l></stanza>
<pb n="18">
<stanza><caption>VII</caption>
<l ln="85      ">And when under the weight of cares for me,
</l><l ln="86      ">&indent;In affection's bower thou seekst repose,
</l><l ln="87      ">&indent;I will gather the myrtle, lilly and rose,
</l><l ln="88      ">To embellish thy resting place for thee.
</l><l ln="89      ">For chastity's reclining couch should be
</l><l ln="90      ">&indent;A sacred shrine, where the gallant daily goes,
</l><l ln="91      ">&indent;A self&hyphen;made vassal, chief of love's heroes
</l><l ln="92      ">Felling the vicious tongue of calumny.
</l><l ln="93      ">When all the means at my command are spent,
</l><l ln="94      ">&indent;Whereof I might make thy sleep softly flow
</l><l ln="95      ">Through sunny dreams, I'll cease to serve, and print
</l><l ln="96      ">&indent;A kiss, love's epilogue, on thy sweet brow,
</l><l ln="97      ">Explanatory of our merriment,
</l><l ln="98      ">&indent;And resign thee to slumbers light and low.</l></stanza>
<stanza><caption>VIII</caption>
<l ln="99      ">Again the long and sombre shadows throw
</l><l ln="100    ">&indent;Their spectre forms across the dreary road;
</l><l ln="101    ">&indent;And their grim quiverings plainly forebode
</l><l ln="102    ">A crisis, and the golden sun, although
</l><l ln="103    ">Fading, has still a rich and brilliant glow,
</l><l ln="104    ">&indent;And his brow of burnished gold throws a robe
</l><l ln="105    ">&indent;Of crimson o'er all; as the grim old ford
</l><l ln="106    ">Between the night and the day he leaps o'er.
</l><l ln="107    ">When tired day slowly succumbs to twilight,
</l><l ln="108    ">&indent;Whose silent curtain, dropping, hides the way
</l><l ln="109    ">From view, and we see cold, dark, gloomy night
</l><l ln="110    ">&indent;In triumph succeed the beautiful day,
</l><l ln="111    ">Until the moon and stars, illumed and bright,
</l><l ln="112    ">&indent;Have martialed themselves in the Milky Way.</l></stanza>
<stanza><caption>IX</caption>
<l ln="113    ">Now the beauties of the sun's after glow
</l><pb n="19">
<l ln="114    ">&indent;Are reflected in yon dazzling arcade,
</l><l ln="115    ">&indent;As legions of stars after stars promenade
</l><l ln="116    ">Down the aisles of the firmament, and throw
</l><l ln="117    ">The glory of their unique order o'er
</l><l ln="118    ">&indent;All; there each in its special orbit stayed,
</l><l ln="119    ">&indent;By the rules of harmony which pervade
</l><l ln="120    ">The universe, has beings of its own,
</l><l ln="121    ">Who looking off on this world of ours, call
</l><l ln="122    ">&indent;It, perchance, a star, as on in its way
</l><l ln="123    ">It goes around the Prince of day, a ball
</l><l ln="124    ">&indent;Of ordinate matter, till ev'ry ray
</l><l ln="125    ">Of the spheres roll in files astronomical,
</l><l ln="126    ">&indent;While in the east the laughing sunbeams play.</l></stanza>
<stanza><caption>X</caption>
<l ln="127    ">Sleep, thou art a workman of skill and art,
</l><l ln="128    ">&indent;The master builder that turneth the arch
</l><l ln="129    ">&indent;Of beauty in feminine form; monarch
</l><l ln="130    ">Of nature's stupendous being and heart,
</l><l ln="131    ">That fills creation to its utmost part,
</l><l ln="132    ">&indent;With energy for its triumphant march,
</l><l ln="133    ">&indent;O'er the blighting forces of death that parch
</l><l ln="134    ">The soul of beauty; aye, the stricken heart
</l><l ln="135    ">Beats stronger after calm repose with thee,
</l><l ln="136    ">&indent;And death is foiled in its triumphant hour,
</l><l ln="137    ">And marks but a point in our destiny,
</l><l ln="138    ">&indent;Where the watch fires burn dimly in life's tower
</l><l ln="139    ">But will blaze with renewed vitality,
</l><l ln="140    ">&indent;Reignited by thy silent power.</l></stanza>
<stanza><caption>XI</caption>
<l ln="141    ">For what is death but calm repose after all?
</l><l ln="142    ">&indent;Sleep, lovely sleep, that finds vitality;
</l><pb n="20">
<l ln="143    ">&indent;Behold! it springs from seed of plant and tree,
</l><l ln="144    ">A living fact, the grave cannot enthrall,
</l><l ln="145    ">Nor annihilation again recall&mdash;
</l><l ln="146    ">&indent;Demonstrated resurrection to me,
</l><l ln="147    ">&indent;Immortal life, man's final destiny;
</l><l ln="148    ">By nature's vital forces ever called
</l><l ln="149    ">To action somewhere in the universe,
</l><l ln="150    ">&indent;After the pause for refreshment and rest,
</l><l ln="151    ">In that realm where the omnivorous nurse
</l><l ln="152    ">&indent;Men call the grave, enfolds all to its breast,
</l><l ln="153    ">Whose stern immutable powers coerce
</l><l ln="154    ">&indent;And all the living maketh a jest.</l></stanza>
<stanza><caption>XII</caption>
<l ln="155    ">Blessed is the man who enters sleep's domain
</l><l ln="156    ">&indent;Of tranquility and majestic ease;
</l><l ln="157    ">&indent;Where refreshing slumbers the weak appease,
</l><l ln="158    ">And with beauty reanimate the inane;
</l><l ln="159    ">Where calumny's shaft and intended pain
</l><l ln="160    ">Are vanished never to return again;
</l><l ln="161    ">&indent;Where society's distinctions release
</l><l ln="162    ">&indent;Their hold, and caste&mdash;that civil disease&mdash;
</l><l ln="163    ">Which has destroyed states and wrecked empires,
</l><l ln="164    ">&indent;Is perpetually barred; there the old
</l><l ln="165    ">Consuming blight of poverty expires,
</l><l ln="166    ">&indent;And of mute inactivity grows cold;
</l><l ln="167    ">When peaceful repose quiets the desires,
</l><l ln="168    ">&indent;And sleep, majestic sleep, fills the household.</l></stanza>
<stanza><caption>XIII</caption>
<l ln="169    ">Come thou, lord of labor, come. I propose
</l><l ln="170    ">&indent;To ally myself with thee, and to have,
</l><l ln="171    ">&indent;Thy powerful hands close these eyes, and pave
</l><pb n="21">
<l ln="172    ">My way to forgetfulness and repose;
</l><l ln="173    ">Teach me how soon forgot are all the woes,
</l><l ln="174    ">&indent;The joys, the triumphs; and all that men crave
</l><l ln="175    ">&indent;Or hope for, love or abhor, when the grave,
</l><l ln="176    ">Ante room to eternity, shall close
</l><l ln="177    ">All the realities of earth to me.
</l><l ln="178    ">&indent;Sweet refreshing slumber, come, my royal
</l><l ln="179    ">Master, come thou, and let me embrace thee.
</l><l ln="180    ">&indent;Oh! come thou, and strengthen me for the toil
</l><l ln="181    ">Of another day; and of eternity
</l><l ln="182    ">&indent;Give me a view, ere my ashes have turned to soil.</l></stanza>
<stanza><caption>XIV</caption>
<l ln="183    ">Sweet the morning after repose with thee,
</l><l ln="184    ">&indent;When the firmament turns from gray to gold
</l><l ln="185    ">&indent;And the radiant starlit sky has rolled
</l><l ln="186    ">Into the archives of day's immensity,
</l><l ln="187    ">And thou awake, seeming fresh from Deity's
</l><l ln="188    ">&indent;Hands come, and we from love's eyes will behold
</l><l ln="189    ">&indent;The first born of all the spheres arise, bold
</l><l ln="190    ">And fearless in his supreme sovereignty
</l><l ln="191    ">O'er all aerial things; but to you,
</l><l ln="192    ">&indent;Last and fairest from the hand of God,
</l><l ln="193    ">He comes on golden wings, a servant true,
</l><l ln="194    ">&indent;Alone illuminating thy abode;
</l><l ln="195    ">There he is at last up the eastern view,
</l><l ln="196    ">&indent;And only for thee creation's beauties hoard.</l></stanza>
<stanza><caption>XV</caption>
<l ln="197    ">Sweep on in thine aerial flight, O sun,
</l><l ln="198    ">&indent;Like shadows old chaos fled before thee,
</l><l ln="199    ">&indent;When thou swung out there over land and sea,
</l><l ln="200    ">The hub of the solar system to run
</l><pb n="22">
<l ln="201    ">The universe; then the morning stars sung
</l><l ln="202    ">&indent;Together while thou set the spheres aglee,
</l><l ln="203    ">&indent;And fixed the measures of their destiny
</l><l ln="204    ">When old time's calendar began to run.
</l><l ln="205    ">But who can fix the measure of thy years,
</l><l ln="206    ">&indent;Or tell when they shall end, as they surely will,
</l><l ln="207    ">For 'tis said thyself shall die, and the spheres
</l><l ln="208    ">&indent;Shall forget their concord and instill
</l><l ln="209    ">In old chaos a new hope; but it appears
</l><l ln="210    ">&indent;It shall not triumph when thou art still.</l></stanza>
<stanza><caption>XVI</caption>
<l ln="211    ">Then Jehovah's supremest attribute
</l><l ln="212    ">&indent;Will light the diamond boulevards of the sky,
</l><l ln="213    ">&indent;And angels of peace and light will fly,
</l><l ln="214    ">On errands of love for thee, and salute
</l><l ln="215    ">Us with shouts of welcome, which will confute
</l><l ln="216    ">&indent;The fears our carnal bodies raised, led by
</l><l ln="217    ">&indent;The prince of night; that father of the lie
</l><l ln="218    ">Which once made us hesitate, and commute
</l><l ln="219    ">The priceless favor of Messiah for him.
</l><l ln="220    ">&indent;But now we see His love in the pathless wood,
</l><l ln="221    ">In rippling stream, and eolian hymn,
</l><l ln="222    ">&indent;In the embellished lea where Flora stood
</l><l ln="223    ">And sowed the flowers in the early spring,
</l><l ln="224    ">&indent;And left the spirit of her sisterhood.</l></stanza>
<stanza><caption>XVII</caption>
<l ln="225    ">Who is the queen of my fancy? Well,
</l><l ln="226    ">&indent;My friend would you really like to know?
</l><l ln="227    ">&indent;She is not yellow, white nor gray, and so
</l><l ln="228    ">Must be something else. I'm afraid to tell,
</l><l ln="229    ">Since all that's mean between heaven and hell,
</l><pb n="23">
<l ln="230    ">&indent;Abhor the color black. She's cherub, though,
</l><l ln="231    ">&indent;And all the fair and the impartial know,
</l><l ln="232    ">She is a beautiful, beautiful angel.
</l><l ln="233    ">I care not what your prejudice, you'll love
</l><l ln="234    ">&indent;Her in your heart, when the light of her dark eyes
</l><l ln="235    ">Beam on you, like the flash of stars above
</l><l ln="236    ">&indent;A dark and rolling cloud; her form complies
</l><l ln="237    ">With all the art the Grecian sculptors prove;
</l><l ln="238    ">&indent;&ldquo;Her voice?&rdquo; A chord escaped from paradise.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>
