<somhead><somauth>Beadle, Samuel Alfred<sombiog>232</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead>MY WISH.</mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200265052</ID><A1>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</A1><T1>MY WISH.</T1><PBL>W. A. Scott</PBL><Y1>1912</Y1><T2>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</attpoet><attidref>C2040214</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>C2040214</attidref><attdbase>African-American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>MY WISH.</mainhead><volhead>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1899</attpubn1><attpubn2>1899</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>232</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">As</hi> I strive to lift the burden,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;When intense becomes the strife,
</l><l ln="3        ">If you are friendly, brother,
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;While the tumult is rife,
</l><l ln="5        ">Is the time above all others,
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;For the helping hand in life.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="7        ">And when I am growing weary,
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;Victory seems in doubt,
</l><l ln="9        ">Then come to my rescue, brother,
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;With praises loud speak out,
</l><l ln="11      ">Do not wait till I have conquered,
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;To raise the cheering shout.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="13      ">If the fight is drawn, my brother,
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;I neither lose nor win,
</l><l ln="15      ">Will you keep your place beside me,
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;Till I try it again,
</l><l ln="17      ">Till I mend my broken armor,
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;And try my hand again?</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="19      ">If the battle goes against me,
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;I'm smitten hip and thigh,
</l><l ln="21      ">It is then and there, my brother,
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;I'd like to have you nigh,
</l><l ln="23      ">With your valor and your courage,
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;And not your sympathy.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="25      ">And when I'm done, my brother,
</l><l ln="26      ">&indent;When my final word is said,
</l><pb n="25">
<l ln="27      ">When I sleep beneath the grasses
</l><l ln="28      ">&indent;Where the daisy lifts its head,
</l><l ln="29      ">In the place of polished marble
</l><l ln="30      ">&indent;Plant the roses instead.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="31      ">You may leave me off your praises,
</l><l ln="32      ">&indent;When they make my humble bed,
</l><l ln="33      ">In the silent land of shadows
</l><l ln="34      ">&indent;With the green sod over head&mdash;
</l><l ln="35      ">If I am forgot while living,
</l><l ln="36      ">&indent;Forget me when I'm dead.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="37      ">Just leave me to the memory
</l><l ln="38      ">&indent;Of him I used to know,
</l><l ln="39      ">Of the friend who stood beside me
</l><l ln="40      ">&indent;So many years ago,
</l><l ln="41      ">When you were quoting calumny
</l><l ln="42      ">&indent;And I was plucking crow.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>
<pb n="34">
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200265053</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Beadle, Samuel Alfred<sombiog>232</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead>I CARE NOT FOR THE MISER'S GOLD.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200265053</ID><A1>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</A1><T1>I CARE NOT FOR THE MISER'S GOLD.</T1><PBL>W. A. Scott</PBL><Y1>1912</Y1><T2>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</attpoet><attidref>C2040215</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>C2040215</attidref><attdbase>African-American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>I CARE NOT FOR THE MISER'S GOLD.</mainhead><volhead>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1899</attpubn1><attpubn2>1899</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>232</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>
<firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">I care</hi> not for the miser's gold,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Nor increased acreage of lands;
</l><l ln="3        ">My neighbor's goods I would not hold
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;Nor wring wealth from his clinched hands.
</l><l ln="5        ">Oh no! My God! I would not have
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;My hands itching for his gold,
</l><l ln="7        ">A higher boon my spirit craves
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;Of Thee. Let me communion hold
</l><l ln="9        ">With these: the good, the great, the free;
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;Aye! let me scale the towering dome
</l><l ln="11      ">Of thought, and feel, and know, and see
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;The highest dome bidding welcome
</l><l ln="13      ">To my continued upward flight;
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;Oh, grant that I may stand amid
</l><l ln="15      ">Men of thought, a man; banish night
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;From my clouded brow, and me rid
</l><l ln="17      ">Of my mental infirmities.
</l><l ln="18      ">Thou Deity of Deities!</l></poem>
</div2>
<pb n="35">
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200265054</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Beadle, Samuel Alfred<sombiog>232</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead>CASTLE BUILDERS.</mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200265054</ID><A1>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</A1><T1>CASTLE BUILDERS.</T1><PBL>W. A. Scott</PBL><Y1>1912</Y1><T2>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</attpoet><attidref>C2040216</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>C2040216</attidref><attdbase>African-American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>CASTLE BUILDERS.</mainhead><volhead>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1899</attpubn1><attpubn2>1899</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>232</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">Many</hi> and many a merry day,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Under the oak tree's shade,
</l><l ln="3        ">We children tripped it out to play,
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;Happy, blithe and gay;
</l><l ln="5        ">Then we built our airy castles high,
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;To occupy&mdash;ah when?
</l><l ln="7        ">&indent;When we were grown to men,
</l><l ln="8        ">Those beautiful, airy castles high,
</l><l ln="9        ">&indent;When we were grown to men.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="10      ">Or down the lane we chased the fly,
</l><l ln="11      ">&indent;That brilliant, gauzy thing,
</l><l ln="12      ">Which seemed a sunbeam floating by,
</l><l ln="13      ">&indent;Blithe and gay as we,
</l><l ln="14      ">When we built those airy castles high,
</l><l ln="15      ">&indent;To occupy&mdash;ah when?
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;When we were grown to men,
</l><l ln="17      ">Those beautiful, airy castles high,
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;When we were grown to men.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="19      ">Alas! the golden years have flown;
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;Also the blithe and gay;
</l><l ln="21      ">But hope's phantoms flit the gloam
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;Just the same today;
</l><l ln="23      ">And we build our airy castles high,
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;To occupy them when
</l><l ln="25      ">&indent;We unite the schemes of men&mdash;
</l><l ln="26      ">You beautiful, airy castles high,
</l><l ln="27      ">&indent;We'll occupy you then.</l></stanza>
<pb n="36">
<stanza><l ln="28      ">And soar again on fancy's wings,
</l><l ln="29      ">&indent;Chasing the rainbows down;
</l><l ln="30      ">Those radiant and dazzling things,
</l><l ln="31      ">&indent;The visionary schemes of men;
</l><l ln="32      ">And build our castles somewhat worse,
</l><l ln="33      ">&indent;Than in the years gone by;
</l><l ln="34      ">&indent;For we shall occupy them when
</l><l ln="35      ">We learn to know man is a farce,
</l><l ln="36      ">&indent;And his promise is a lie.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200265055</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Beadle, Samuel Alfred<sombiog>232</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead>THE PYRAMID.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200265055</ID><A1>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</A1><T1>THE PYRAMID.</T1><PBL>W. A. Scott</PBL><Y1>1912</Y1><T2>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</attpoet><attidref>C2040217</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>C2040217</attidref><attdbase>African-American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>THE PYRAMID.</mainhead><volhead>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1899</attpubn1><attpubn2>1899</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>232</attautid><litpack></litpack><attgenre>Lyric</attgenre></newatts>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">The</hi> pyramid through ages past,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Through all their tempest, storm and blast,
</l><l ln="3        ">Held its apex up to grasp
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;The elements.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="5        ">Three thousand years, long and fleet,
</l><l ln="6        ">Have struck their colors at its feet,
</l><l ln="7        ">Ten thousand more its strength shall meet
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;Till time is done.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="9        ">Where is the tower Babel built?
</l><l ln="10      ">Where is Tyre's crimson hilt?
</l><l ln="11      ">Judea's temple. and the guilt
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;Her neighbors' knew?</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="13      ">They're gone at oblivion's call&mdash;
</l><l ln="14      ">Old Egypt's skill survives them all&mdash;
</l><l ln="15      ">Yet in the art of Pharaoh's pall
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;The Egyptian lives.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>
<pb n="37">
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200265056</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Beadle, Samuel Alfred<sombiog>232</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead>JOE'S FARM.</mainhead> <attbytes>4Kb</attbytes><volhead>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200265056</ID><A1>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</A1><T1>JOE'S FARM.</T1><PBL>W. A. Scott</PBL><Y1>1912</Y1><T2>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</attpoet><attidref>C2040218</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>C2040218</attidref><attdbase>African-American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>JOE'S FARM.</mainhead><volhead>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>4Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1899</attpubn1><attpubn2>1899</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>232</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">Many</hi> aud many a year has gone
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Since I was cleared by Joe,
</l><l ln="3        ">Who plowed me up and planted corn,
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;To see it shoot and grow.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="5        ">He built an old Virginia fence
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;Out there where the wires run;
</l><l ln="7        ">And worked, he said, in self&hyphen;defense,
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;From sunny sun to sun.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="9        ">He planted peas between the rows,
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;And pumpkins here and there;
</l><l ln="11      ">And where that patch of briar grows
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;He set out deep the pear.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="13      ">And further on the apple tree,
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;And the peach orchard there;
</l><l ln="15      ">With worthy pride embellished me
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;With fruit trees ev'rywhere.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="17      ">And placed around the orchard, sir,
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;Were hives and hives of bees;
</l><l ln="19      ">In the piggery the hogs were;
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;In the pasture, the beeves.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="21      ">And fiery steeds, and all that go
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;To make your farm a home;
</l><l ln="23      ">But that which was most prized by Joe
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;Was his broad fertile loam.</l></stanza>
<pb n="38">
<stanza><l ln="25      ">He kept me fertilized and tiled,
</l><l ln="26      ">&indent;With ditches deep and wide,
</l><l ln="27      ">And never let the floods run wild,
</l><l ln="28      ">&indent;Nor stream it down my side.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="29      ">And where the gullies would have been,
</l><l ln="30      ">&indent;Near by he planted trees;
</l><l ln="31      ">Then there the grass grew bright and green,
</l><l ln="32      ">&indent;And there would play the breeze.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="33      ">But Joe has long since passed away,
</l><l ln="34      ">&indent;And others master here;
</l><l ln="35      ">Yet since that sad and gloomy day
</l><l ln="36      ">&indent;I've lordless been and drear.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="37      ">And where was once the verdant knoll,
</l><l ln="38      ">&indent;Gullies are yawning wide;
</l><l ln="39      ">And when it rains the waters roll
</l><l ln="40      ">&indent;In torrents down my side.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="41      ">Here in the flats the briars grow,
</l><l ln="42      ">&indent;The thistles on the hills;
</l><l ln="43      ">And where the gin wheels used to go
</l><l ln="44      ">&indent;Are a few rotten sills.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="45      ">The gentleman that's master now
</l><l ln="46      ">&indent;Says farming does not pay;
</l><l ln="47      ">He neither drives nor holds the plow,
</l><l ln="48      ">And values not his clay.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="49      ">When the master of this place was Joe
</l><l ln="50      ">&indent;And cotton king of crops,
</l><l ln="51      ">I've seen the white and red blooms blow
</l><l ln="52      ">&indent;On miles of my sunny tops.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="53      ">And in the fall the fleecy stuff
</l><l ln="54      ">&indent;Would fill the earth like snow,
</l><l ln="55      ">The harvesters would cry enough,
</l><l ln="56      ">&indent;And farming it paid Joe.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>
<pb n="39">
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200265057</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Beadle, Samuel Alfred<sombiog>232</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead>AFTER CHURCH.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200265057</ID><A1>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</A1><T1>AFTER CHURCH.</T1><PBL>W. A. Scott</PBL><Y1>1912</Y1><T2>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</attpoet><attidref>C2040219</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>C2040219</attidref><attdbase>African-American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>AFTER CHURCH.</mainhead><volhead>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1899</attpubn1><attpubn2>1899</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>232</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">Yes</hi>, May and I are friends,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Lovers, many have said;
</l><l ln="3        ">For down the lane and o'er the lea
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;To church we often tread,
</l><l ln="5        ">In that careless sort of way,
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;That leads to love, they say;
</l><l ln="7        ">And after church we often search
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;For garlands by the way.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="9        ">Yes, May and I are friends,
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;And something more, they say;
</l><l ln="11      ">Because along the curved strand,
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;Where we sat the other day,
</l><l ln="13      ">I simply wrote her name,
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;And wrote it o'er again;
</l><l ln="15      ">When after church we stopped to search
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;For shells along the main.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="17      ">More than friends are we,
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;My bonny May and I;
</l><l ln="19      ">At least that's what our neighbors say
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;Whene'er they pass us by,
</l><l ln="21      ">They smile and wink their eye,
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;And set their necks awry:
</l><l ln="23      ">When after church we stop to search
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;For heart's ease, May and I.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>
<pb n="40">
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200265058</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Beadle, Samuel Alfred<sombiog>232</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead>WORDS.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200265058</ID><A1>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</A1><T1>WORDS.</T1><PBL>W. A. Scott</PBL><Y1>1912</Y1><T2>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</attpoet><attidref>C2040220</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>C2040220</attidref><attdbase>African-American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>WORDS.</mainhead><volhead>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1899</attpubn1><attpubn2>1899</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>232</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">Words</hi> are but leaves to the tree of mind;
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Where breezy fancy plays;
</l><l ln="3        ">Or echoes from the souls which find
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;Expression's subtle ways.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="5        ">A beaming lamp to idea's feet
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;Where sentinel thought abides;
</l><l ln="7        ">Or a guide to the soul's retreat,
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;Where master man presides.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="9        ">A jewel trembling on the tongue,
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;The index of the heart;
</l><l ln="11      ">The black mask from the spirit wrung.
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;Revealing every part.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="13      ">A ship upon the sea of life,
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;With all her sails aswell;
</l><l ln="15      ">Her cargo being the bread of life,
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;Or the cindered dross of hell.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>
<pb n="41">
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200265059</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Beadle, Samuel Alfred<sombiog>232</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead>LINES ON THE DEATH OF A FRIEND.</mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200265059</ID><A1>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</A1><T1>LINES ON THE DEATH OF A FRIEND.</T1><PBL>W. A. Scott</PBL><Y1>1912</Y1><T2>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</attpoet><attidref>C2040221</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>C2040221</attidref><attdbase>African-American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>LINES ON THE DEATH OF A FRIEND.</mainhead><volhead>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1899</attpubn1><attpubn2>1899</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>232</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">Life</hi> is a mysterious thing.
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;It comes we know not whence,
</l><l ln="3        ">And leaves us on a rapid wing
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;For an absence immense.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="5        ">Just yester morn I had a friend,
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;Cheerful, brilliant and gay;
</l><l ln="7        ">Today grim Death announced his end,
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;And bore him hence away.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="9        ">Away into that dark region,
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;From kindred, friend and foe,
</l><l ln="11      ">To join the numberless legion
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;Of men who went before.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="13      ">Who, now, will cheer the broken hearted,
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;Or shield them from Death's wrath,
</l><l ln="15      ">Since the strong, the brave, has departed,
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;And left a corpse in the path?</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="17      ">He was adorned with honor's star,
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;Had conquered all but fate;
</l><l ln="19      ">Death's wing became his palace car
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;And bore him to heaven's gate.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="21      ">Sleep on, dear friend; thou art not dead;
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;Much labor bids thee rest
</l><l ln="23      ">Profoundly in thy narrow bed,
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;Of mother earth the guest.</l></stanza>
<pb n="42">
<stanza><l ln="25      ">The good, the great in eminence,
</l><l ln="26      ">&indent;The famous, and the proud,
</l><l ln="27      ">Shall join thee, shorn of this pretense,
</l><l ln="28      ">&indent;Clothed only with a shroud.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="29      ">Ambition, pride and hope may rise
</l><l ln="30      ">&indent;Towering up Fame's dazzling peaks;
</l><l ln="31      ">Yet they but find in glory's skies
</l><l ln="32      ">&indent;The bier where valor sleeps.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>
<pb n="60">
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200265060</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Beadle, Samuel Alfred<sombiog>232</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead>TO THE DAISY.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200265060</ID><A1>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</A1><T1>TO THE DAISY.</T1><PBL>W. A. Scott</PBL><Y1>1912</Y1><T2>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</attpoet><attidref>C2040222</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>C2040222</attidref><attdbase>African-American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>TO THE DAISY.</mainhead><volhead>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1899</attpubn1><attpubn2>1899</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>232</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">No</hi>, the cold damp earth could not restrain thee,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Nor the bleak north winds retard thy coming;
</l><l ln="3        ">&indent;For first on the green where the lambs are running,
</l><l ln="4        ">And down where the rushing brooklet doth flee,
</l><l ln="5        ">In its musical cadence on to the sea,
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;Thy sweet face has been modestly turning
</l><l ln="7        ">&indent;Its delicate features up to the sunning,
</l><l ln="8        ">And throwing its fragrance over the lea,
</l><l ln="9        ">In a wild and most exuberant way.
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;Oh, I love thee, wee blue eyed daisy fair!
</l><l ln="11      ">And I wish thou might blow out there for aye.
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;Filled with loveliness, perfuming the air,
</l><l ln="13      ">And alluring me from the broad highway,
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;To gather garlands for my lady fair.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="15      ">Thou sit'st upon the meadow's lap of green,
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;Like smiles upon the face of a sleeping babe,
</l><l ln="17      ">&indent;And the zephyrs sighing through the everglade,
</l><l ln="18      ">Waft thy perfumes to the winding stream
</l><l ln="19      ">That lies at thy feet a beautiful sheen;
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;By the skill of the Master cunningly made,
</l><l ln="21      ">&indent;To catch the likeness of my dark eyed maid
</l><l ln="22      ">As she gathers her garlands there, I ween;
</l><l ln="23      ">Thy Circean beauty bewilders me,
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;For truly, I am curious to know
</l><l ln="25      ">Why the most delicate flowers that be,
</l><l ln="26      ">&indent;Upon lawn, heather and bough, should first blow,
</l><l ln="27      ">Fairest and sweetest in their modesty,
</l><l ln="28      ">&indent;Of all the beautiful flowers that grow.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>
<pb n="61">
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200265061</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Beadle, Samuel Alfred<sombiog>232</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead>THE FATE OF ALL.</mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200265061</ID><A1>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</A1><T1>THE FATE OF ALL.</T1><PBL>W. A. Scott</PBL><Y1>1912</Y1><T2>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</attpoet><attidref>C2040223</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>C2040223</attidref><attdbase>African-American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>THE FATE OF ALL.</mainhead><volhead>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1899</attpubn1><attpubn2>1899</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>232</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">They'll</hi> bring when we are dead, perchance,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Some flowers from their garden, friend;
</l><l ln="3        ">And place them where Time's cruel lance
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;Has marked for us, for all, the end.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="5        ">They'll drop upon our bier a tear,
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;And close for us our eyes; and then
</l><l ln="7        ">They will leave us forgotten here,
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;Till time has run its course with men.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="9        ">If thought of us survives a day,
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;A month, a year or century,
</l><l ln="11      ">Still we shall be forgot for aye;
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;For time consumes all memory.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="13      ">If Love should rear her shaft of stone,
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;To mark our little mound of dust,
</l><l ln="15      ">The granitic fate too well is known&mdash;
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;It shall decay to mould with us.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="17      ">A few brief years may yet remain
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;To us on this delightful shore,
</l><l ln="19      ">Then in the silent land's domain
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;We shall rest in peace forevermore.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="21      ">The generations yet to come,
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;Creation's vast immensity,
</l><l ln="23      ">Shall find with us a common home,
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;For commonage's our destiny.</l></stanza>
<pb n="62">
<stanza><l ln="25      ">The vast expanse of all the deep
</l><l ln="26      ">&indent;Shall one day pause and cease to roll;
</l><l ln="27      ">The liquid grave where millions sleep
</l><l ln="28      ">&indent;Shall itself give up its soul.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="29      ">When oblivion reigns supreme,
</l><l ln="30      ">&indent;Down the endless aisles of chaos,
</l><l ln="31      ">All things become alike gangrene,
</l><l ln="32      ">&indent;In the land where spirit leaves us.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200265062</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Beadle, Samuel Alfred<sombiog>232</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead>TO A JILT.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200265062</ID><A1>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</A1><T1>TO A JILT.</T1><PBL>W. A. Scott</PBL><Y1>1912</Y1><T2>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</attpoet><attidref>C2040224</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>C2040224</attidref><attdbase>African-American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>TO A JILT.</mainhead><volhead>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1899</attpubn1><attpubn2>1899</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>232</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">Why</hi> did you not tell me your heart is stone,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Where hope, nor joy, nor pleasures abide;
</l><l ln="3        ">At whose granite base lies broken my own,
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;Shorn of its faith and bereft of its pride?</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="5        ">Yes, I recall, you said something of this,
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;But the light of your eye, the smile of your face,
</l><l ln="7        ">Led me to confide in the promised bliss
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;You taught me to seek of your assumed grace.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="9        ">And I dreamed not that one with features so fair,
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;And a form which truly the angels envy,
</l><l ln="11      ">Could weave so well the treacherous snare
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;Of vice, and pride, and perjured frenzy.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="13      ">Fare thee well! Satanic creature, adieu!
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;Think no more of him who now tries to wean
</l><l ln="15      ">His soul from squandering his all on you&mdash;
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;Thou false in friendship, in wedlock a fiend!</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>
<pb n="63">
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200265063</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Beadle, Samuel Alfred<sombiog>232</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead><hi r="roman">LINES</hi>. Suggested by the Assaults made on the Negro Soldiers as they passed
through the south on their way to and from our war with Spain.</mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200265063</ID><A1>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</A1><T1>LINES. Suggested by the Assaults made on the Negro Soldiers as they passed through the south on their way to and from our war with Spain.</T1><PBL>W. A. Scott</PBL><Y1>1912</Y1><T2>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</attpoet><attidref>C2040225</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>C2040225</attidref><attdbase>African-American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>LINES. Suggested by the Assaults made on the Negro Soldiers as they passed through the south on their way to and from our war with Spain.</mainhead><volhead>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1899</attpubn1><attpubn2>1899</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>232</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">How</hi> I love my country you have heard,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;And I would you were noble and free
</l><l ln="3        ">In spirit and deed, as in word,
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;And your boasted humanity.
</l><l ln="5        ">I love you, my country, I do,&mdash;
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;Here's a heart, a soul that is thine,
</l><l ln="7        ">Pregnant with devotion for you,
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;And blind to your faults as to mine.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="9        ">The standard of morals is high;
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;When fixed by my brother for me,
</l><l ln="11      ">It goes towering up to the sky
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;With a dazzling purity.
</l><l ln="13      ">For a bench he sits on a skull,
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;And is a judge austere and stern,
</l><l ln="15      ">With whom my demurrers are null,
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;And my pleadings, though just, are spurned.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="17      ">I've carried your flag to the front
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;Through pestilence, battles and storms;
</l><l ln="19      ">Of the carnage of war took the blunt,
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;Obeyed your command, &ldquo;Carry arms!&rdquo;
</l><l ln="21      ">And gone with you down to the death,
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;With the thorns of caste on my head;
</l><l ln="23      ">Defended your home and your hearth,
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;And wept o'er the bier of your dead.</l></stanza>
<pb n="64">
<stanza><l ln="25      ">As the smoke of the fight goes by,
</l><l ln="26      ">&indent;And the bugle calls to repose,
</l><l ln="27      ">By my countryman's hands I die,
</l><l ln="28      ">&indent;As well as by the hands of its foes;
</l><l ln="29      ">Yet I love you, my country, I do,
</l><l ln="30      ">&indent;Here's a heart, a soul that is thine,
</l><l ln="31      ">Pregnant with devotion for you,
</l><l ln="32      ">&indent;And blind to your faults as to mine.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200265064</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Beadle, Samuel Alfred<sombiog>232</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead>MY LIST OF BEAUTIFUL THINGS.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200265064</ID><A1>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</A1><T1>MY LIST OF BEAUTIFUL THINGS.</T1><PBL>W. A. Scott</PBL><Y1>1912</Y1><T2>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</attpoet><attidref>C2040226</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>C2040226</attidref><attdbase>African-American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>MY LIST OF BEAUTIFUL THINGS.</mainhead><volhead>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1899</attpubn1><attpubn2>1899</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>232</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">A list</hi> of my beautiful things?&rdquo;
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Well, have you seen my Evylin;
</l><l ln="3        ">&indent;The beautiful, beautiful Evylin?
</l><l ln="4        ">She's my list of beautiful things.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="5        ">A world of beautiful things is she,
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;Grand! chaste! personified
</l><l ln="7        ">&indent;Love she stands in purity's pride
</l><l ln="8        ">And thinks of me, and thinks of me.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="9        ">Poems of ethical thought is she,
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;Divinely sung on every page;
</l><l ln="11      ">&indent;All her womanly heart engaged
</l><l ln="12      ">With love of me, with love of me.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="13      ">My list of beautiful things,
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;None were ever so sublimely grand,
</l><l ln="15      ">&indent;To her I give my heart and hand,
</l><l ln="16      ">And all the wealth my labor brings.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>
<pb n="65">
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200265065</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Beadle, Samuel Alfred<sombiog>232</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead>A MESSAGE FOR JANETT.</mainhead> <attbytes>6Kb</attbytes><volhead>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200265065</ID><A1>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</A1><T1>A MESSAGE FOR JANETT.</T1><PBL>W. A. Scott</PBL><Y1>1912</Y1><T2>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</attpoet><attidref>C2040227</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>C2040227</attidref><attdbase>African-American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>A MESSAGE FOR JANETT.</mainhead><volhead>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>6Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1899</attpubn1><attpubn2>1899</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>232</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">Far</hi> away where the raging sea goes,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;In the islands of the sea,
</l><l ln="3        ">There our brave and daring heroes
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;Fought the battles of the free;
</l><l ln="5        ">From the hands of arrogant Spain
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;Struck the sword of tyranny,
</l><l ln="7        ">&indent;On the plains of El Caney.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="8        ">But o'er the halo of our glory
</l><l ln="9        ">&indent;Falls the mem'ry of our brave,
</l><l ln="10      ">Stalwart men, all maimed and gory,
</l><l ln="11      ">&indent;Sleeping in a foreign grave,
</l><l ln="12      ">Where the grim Spanish armament,
</l><l ln="13      ">&indent;And her gallant men of war,
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;Threw death's missiles wide and far.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="15      ">There among the dead and dying
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;Lay a victim of their rage,
</l><l ln="17      ">By a Spanish block house lying,
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;Amid the battle's carnage.
</l><l ln="19      ">He yields to death while glory weeps;
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;But conquers its agony,
</l><l ln="21      ">&indent;And recks not of its misery.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="22      ">Now his mind on fancy's pinion
</l><l ln="23      ">&indent;Wings its flight to friends and home,
</l><l ln="24      ">Takes its leave of war's dominion,
</l><l ln="25      ">&indent;Flutters down the vista gloam;
</l><l ln="26      ">Till again his friends and loved ones
</l><pb n="66">
<l ln="27      ">&indent;Shout their welcome in his ear,
</l><l ln="28      ">&indent;O'er his comrade's martial cheer.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="29      ">But his end came nearer, nearer;
</l><l ln="30      ">&indent;Yet he raised his manly head,
</l><l ln="31      ">And in language somewhat clearer
</l><l ln="32      ">&indent;Called his comrade near, and said,
</l><l ln="33      ">&ldquo;Comrade, if you should live it through
</l><l ln="34      ">&indent;Tell them how we met the Don,
</l><l ln="35      ">&indent;Fought for human rights and won;</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="36      ">&ldquo;Strove to place our standard higher
</l><l ln="37      ">&indent;On the ramparts of the free,
</l><l ln="38      ">Defied the Spaniard's deadly fire
</l><l ln="39      ">&indent;And died for humanity;
</l><l ln="40      ">Tell them of our negro heroes,
</l><l ln="41      ">&indent;Of the valiant black brigade,
</l><l ln="42      ">&indent;And the gallant charge it made.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="43      ">&ldquo;You remember there's another,
</l><l ln="44      ">&indent;Dearer far than all to me&mdash;
</l><l ln="45      ">Comrade, don't forget my mother,
</l><l ln="46      ">&indent;For she is all expectancy.
</l><l ln="47      ">Tell her that I met death bravely,
</l><l ln="48      ">&indent;With the red sod for a bed,
</l><l ln="49      ">&indent;And &lsquo;Old Glory&rsquo; over head.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="50      ">&ldquo;You will find her by the hearthstone
</l><l ln="51      ">&indent;Near the northern Mexic coast&mdash;
</l><l ln="52      ">Dreaming that I'm coming home,
</l><l ln="53      ">&indent;And the Spaniard's cause is lost.&mdash;
</l><l ln="54      ">&lsquo;What answer shall you make to her?&rsquo;
</l><l ln="55      ">&indent;Tell her that she lost a son,
</l><l ln="56      ">&indent;But the day was nobly won.</l></stanza>
<pb n="67">
<stanza><l ln="57      ">&ldquo;Then you'll take a message for me
</l><l ln="58      ">&indent;To Janett, across the main;
</l><l ln="59      ">There she's bravely waiting for me,
</l><l ln="60      ">&indent;But we'll never meet again
</l><l ln="61      ">On that undulating landscape,
</l><l ln="62      ">&indent;Rolling onward, copse and lea,
</l><l ln="63      ">&indent;In their rustic purity.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="64      ">&ldquo;Where a laughing, rippling streamlet,
</l><l ln="65      ">&indent;Playing with the golden sands,
</l><l ln="66      ">Loiters by the peaceful hamlet,
</l><l ln="67      ">&indent;Winds along the fallow lands,
</l><l ln="68      ">Through a green and varied landscape,
</l><l ln="69      ">&indent;There Janett awaits for me,
</l><l ln="70      ">&indent;In a cottage near the sea.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="71      ">&ldquo;In a garden, sweetly laden
</l><l ln="72      ">&indent;With the roses newly blown,
</l><l ln="73      ">There the comely, gracious maiden
</l><l ln="74      ">&indent;Stands before her cottage home;
</l><l ln="75      ">Now she moves across the landscape
</l><l ln="76      ">&indent;Through the copse and o'er the lea.
</l><l ln="77      ">&indent;See! she comes to welcome me!</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="78      ">&ldquo;You will know her by her lashes,
</l><l ln="79      ">&indent;Fringing eyes as dark as jet;
</l><l ln="80      ">And her curly raven tresses&mdash;
</l><l ln="81      ">&indent;You can't miss my fair Janett,
</l><l ln="82      ">With her beautiful curved neck,
</l><l ln="83      ">&indent;And the rare angelic grace
</l><l ln="84      ">&indent;Of her motion, form and face.&rdquo;</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="85      ">Here his voice grew faint and broken,
</l><l ln="86      ">&indent;But his face with rapture shone,
</l><pb n="68">
<l ln="87      ">As he held aloft the token
</l><l ln="88      ">&indent;Which he through the fight had borne;
</l><l ln="89      ">'Twas our old and riven ensign,
</l><l ln="90      ">&indent;That his clotted blood did blur&mdash;
</l><l ln="91      ">&indent;This the message sent to her.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200265066</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Beadle, Samuel Alfred<sombiog>232</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead>MY SUBURBAN GIRL.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200265066</ID><A1>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</A1><T1>MY SUBURBAN GIRL.</T1><PBL>W. A. Scott</PBL><Y1>1912</Y1><T2>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</attpoet><attidref>C2040228</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>C2040228</attidref><attdbase>African-American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>MY SUBURBAN GIRL.</mainhead><volhead>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1899</attpubn1><attpubn2>1899</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>232</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">I know</hi> a sweet suburban girl,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;She's witty, bright and brief;
</l><l ln="3        ">With dimples in her cheeks; and pearl
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;In rubies set, for teeth.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="5        ">Beneath her glossy raven hair
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;There beams the hazel eye,
</l><l ln="7        ">Bright as the star of evening there
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;Where the yellow sunbeams die.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="9        ">Her breath is like a flower blown,
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;In fragrance and perfume;
</l><l ln="11      ">Her voice seems from the blissful throne
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;Where their harps the angels tune.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="13      ">Her waist is just a trifle more
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;Than a cubit in its girth;
</l><l ln="15      ">But when there my arms I throw,
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;I've all there is of earth.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="17      ">And when she turns her dimpled cheek
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;Toward me for a kiss,
</l><l ln="19      ">I lose expression&mdash;cannot speak&mdash;
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;And take all there is of bliss.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>
<pb n="69">
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200265067</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Beadle, Samuel Alfred<sombiog>232</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead>THE SOUTHERN GIRL.</mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200265067</ID><A1>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</A1><T1>THE SOUTHERN GIRL.</T1><PBL>W. A. Scott</PBL><Y1>1912</Y1><T2>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</attpoet><attidref>C2040229</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>C2040229</attidref><attdbase>African-American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>THE SOUTHERN GIRL.</mainhead><volhead>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1899</attpubn1><attpubn2>1899</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>232</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">The</hi> fairest thing on land or sea
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Is the Southern girl, to me.
</l><l ln="3        ">&indent;You should see her when the stars
</l><l ln="4        ">Come studding all the sky;
</l><l ln="5        ">And feel her beaming eye
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;On you when the moon is full&mdash;
</l><l ln="7        ">Fairest of all that's fair is she,
</l><l ln="8        ">The Southern girl, to me.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="9        ">You should hear her laugh by night,
</l><l ln="10      ">In the moonlight clear and bright,
</l><l ln="11      ">&indent;When the zephyrs light and low,
</l><l ln="12      ">Across the gardens steal,
</l><l ln="13      ">To play with the Marechal&hyphen;Neil,
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;And caress the beautiful girl&mdash;
</l><l ln="15      ">Fairest of all that's fair is she,
</l><l ln="16      ">The Southern girl, to me.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="17      ">Beneath the Marechal&hyphen;Neil by night,
</l><l ln="18      ">In the hush of the dead twilight,
</l><l ln="19      ">&indent;You should meet the Southern girl;
</l><l ln="20      ">And hear the angel sing,
</l><l ln="21      ">The bonny angel sing;
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;And feast on wit, and joy, and love&mdash;
</l><l ln="23      ">Fairest of all that's fair is she,
</l><l ln="24      ">The Southern girl, to me.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="25      ">The vocal enwoven beauty
</l><l ln="26      ">Of her graces ever cheers me,
</l><pb n="70">
<l ln="27      ">&indent;As I listen to the cadence
</l><l ln="28      ">Of her metrical airs,
</l><l ln="29      ">Whene'er she trills and dares
</l><l ln="30      ">&indent;Some melodious chord to make&mdash;
</l><l ln="31      ">Fairest of all that's fair is she,
</l><l ln="32      ">The Southern girl, to me.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="33      ">After the wooing and merry days,
</l><l ln="34      ">Go with her through her toiling ways,
</l><l ln="35      ">&indent;As mother, and wife, and friend;
</l><l ln="36      ">Learn the iron will,
</l><l ln="37      ">The courage and the skill
</l><l ln="38      ">&indent;Of the typical Southern girl&mdash;
</l><l ln="39      ">Fairest of all that's fair is she,
</l><l ln="40      ">The Southern girl, to me.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200265068</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Beadle, Samuel Alfred<sombiog>232</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead>ELLA'S DANCE.</mainhead> <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><volhead>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200265068</ID><A1>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</A1><T1>ELLA'S DANCE.</T1><PBL>W. A. Scott</PBL><Y1>1912</Y1><T2>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</attpoet><attidref>C2040230</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>C2040230</attidref><attdbase>African-American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>ELLA'S DANCE.</mainhead><volhead>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>1Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1899</attpubn1><attpubn2>1899</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>232</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">Come</hi>, tripping, tripping, tripping, oh,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">On the light fantastic toe;
</l><l ln="3        ">And we'll tread the royal measure,
</l><l ln="4        ">Down the aisles of wit and pleasure,
</l><l ln="5        ">Gilding softly, sweetly so,
</l><l ln="6        ">On the nimble, nimble toe.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="7        ">Come, lightly, lightly, lightly, oh!
</l><l ln="8        ">Press me softly as we go,
</l><l ln="9        ">Playfully skipping to and fro,
</l><l ln="10      ">As round, and round we reel and go,
</l><l ln="11      ">Gliding softly, sweetly so,
</l><l ln="12      ">On the nimble, nimble toe.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>
<pb n="71">
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200265069</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Beadle, Samuel Alfred<sombiog>232</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead>FLORA.</mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200265069</ID><A1>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</A1><T1>FLORA.</T1><PBL>W. A. Scott</PBL><Y1>1912</Y1><T2>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</attpoet><attidref>C2040231</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>C2040231</attidref><attdbase>African-American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>FLORA.</mainhead><volhead>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1899</attpubn1><attpubn2>1899</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>232</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">I sought</hi> her in the woodland
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Where the dogwood blossoms blow,
</l><l ln="3        ">And thought I had her cornered
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;Where the little rill doth flow,
</l><l ln="5        ">&indent;Laughs and sings, laughs and sings,
</l><l ln="6        ">Sweeping over golden sands,
</l><l ln="7        ">Like a living thing
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;On burnished silver wings.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="9        ">But the cunning elf escaped me,
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;And left me standing there,
</l><l ln="11      ">Bewildered by the cadence
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;Of her music in the air;
</l><l ln="13      ">&indent;In the air, in the air
</l><l ln="14      ">The poesy of nature,
</l><l ln="15      ">Struck by the feathered tribe,
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;Ran lyrical ev'rywhere.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="17      ">Till fancy caught her smiling
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;In the budding of the trees,
</l><l ln="19      ">Where tiny little leaflets
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;Unfolded to the breeze,
</l><l ln="21      ">&indent;To the breeze, to the breeze,
</l><l ln="22      ">When Flora came a&hyphen;riding
</l><l ln="23      ">A sunbeam for a steed,
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;Down the floral highways of the leas.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="25      ">And the cunning elf flew onward,
</l><l ln="26      ">&indent;With magical little wand
</l><pb n="72">
<l ln="27      ">Painting up the butter cups
</l><l ln="28      ">&indent;Beside her as she ran,
</l><l ln="29      ">&indent;As she ran, as she ran;
</l><l ln="30      ">Till her prancing steed stood still
</l><l ln="31      ">Entangled in the snare
</l><l ln="32      ">&indent;On my lady's cheeks of tan.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="33      ">You cunning little elfin,
</l><l ln="34      ">&indent;I have sought you ev'rywhere
</l><l ln="35      ">To find you 'neath the tresses
</l><l ln="36      ">&indent;Of a girl's disheveled hair;
</l><l ln="37      ">&indent;Lady fair, graced and rare.
</l><l ln="38      ">When you stoop to plant the rose
</l><l ln="39      ">You but set its colors
</l><l ln="40      ">&indent;In your cheeks, my lady fair.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200265070</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Beadle, Samuel Alfred<sombiog>232</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead>NANNIE IS A BONNIE MAID.</mainhead> <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><volhead>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200265070</ID><A1>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</A1><T1>NANNIE IS A BONNIE MAID.</T1><PBL>W. A. Scott</PBL><Y1>1912</Y1><T2>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</attpoet><attidref>C2040232</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>C2040232</attidref><attdbase>African-American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>NANNIE IS A BONNIE MAID.</mainhead><volhead>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>1Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1899</attpubn1><attpubn2>1899</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>232</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">Nannie</hi>, she is dearer far
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Than all the girls I know,
</l><l ln="3        ">For when the cook deserts her ma
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;And swears she'll work no more,
</l><l ln="5        ">She puts her latest music by
</l><l ln="6        ">And bakes an apple pie.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="7        ">Nannie is a bonnie maid,
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;There's none so neat and fair,
</l><l ln="9        ">As she when dressed in Wesson plaid,
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;And banged her glossy hair,
</l><l ln="11      ">With all her silken skirts put by,
</l><l ln="12      ">While she serves the apple pie.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>
<pb n="73">
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200265071</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Beadle, Samuel Alfred<sombiog>232</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead>MY PRAYER.</mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200265071</ID><A1>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</A1><T1>MY PRAYER.</T1><PBL>W. A. Scott</PBL><Y1>1912</Y1><T2>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</attpoet><attidref>C2040233</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>C2040233</attidref><attdbase>African-American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>MY PRAYER.</mainhead><volhead>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1899</attpubn1><attpubn2>1899</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>232</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">My</hi> Savior, in life's ebb and flow,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">In its turmoil, in its glow,
</l><l ln="3        ">In its triumph, in its woe,
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;Through its changes guard Thou me.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="5        ">I am weak and poor and blind,
</l><l ln="6        ">And oft in my weakness I find
</l><l ln="7        ">Vile sin has stol'n my peace of mind.
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;And driven me, Oh Lord, from Thee.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="9        ">Eternal One, hide not Thy face,
</l><l ln="10      ">But grant me mercy, love and grace,
</l><l ln="11      ">And in Thy providence a place
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;Of security and rest.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="13      ">I know Thou art rich without me,
</l><l ln="14      ">That one, God, the Spirit and Thee,
</l><l ln="15      ">Is th' eternal Deity;
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;And angels are Thy worshipers.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="17      ">In Thy hands love and justice dwell,
</l><l ln="18      ">And the hosts of light, earth and hell
</l><l ln="19      ">Obedient to Thy will must swell
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;The long roll at the judgment call.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="21      ">Lord, I know when the bleeding heart
</l><l ln="22      ">Looks up to Thee, Thou wilt impart
</l><l ln="23      ">Upon each ruptured broken part
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;The soothing balm of Thy sweet love.</l></stanza>
<pb n="74">
<stanza><l ln="25      ">And when estranged are all earth's friends
</l><l ln="26      ">And the gloom of rejection still tends
</l><l ln="27      ">To obstruct my way, Thou wilt send
</l><l ln="28      ">&indent;Me Thy comforter from above.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="29      ">And if fortune at last should beam
</l><l ln="30      ">Upon my obscure path, a gleam
</l><l ln="31      ">Of sunshine from Thy upper realm,
</l><l ln="32      ">&indent;I know the sunshine, Lord, is Thine.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="33      ">Lord, I would learn to love mankind,
</l><l ln="34      ">Through love of him a passage find
</l><l ln="35      ">To a rich and bright and purer mind,
</l><l ln="36      ">&indent;And home and rest at last with Thee.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>
<pb n="83">
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200265072</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Beadle, Samuel Alfred<sombiog>232</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead>BIOGRAPHIA.</mainhead> <attbytes>10Kb</attbytes><volhead>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200265072</ID><A1>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</A1><T1>BIOGRAPHIA.</T1><PBL>W. A. Scott</PBL><Y1>1912</Y1><T2>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</attpoet><attidref>C2040234</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>C2040234</attidref><attdbase>African-American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>BIOGRAPHIA.</mainhead><volhead>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>10Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1899</attpubn1><attpubn2>1899</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>232</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">I saw</hi> sweep out of the unknown
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">A worthy sunlit bark, alone,
</l><l ln="3        ">By eddies dallied and then thrown
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;Down with Life's stream.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="5        ">And on its frail though radiant prow,
</l><l ln="6        ">&ldquo;Consigned to the unknown art thou,&rdquo;
</l><l ln="7        ">Was stamped by Him, Who then, as now,
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;Directs the end.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="9        ">There went with it a being of hope&mdash;
</l><l ln="10      ">A radiant being of hope,
</l><l ln="11      ">An ethereal philanthrope,
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;Somewhat divine.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="13      ">She steered the craft hard by the shore&mdash;
</l><l ln="14      ">I heard the stroke of her golden oar,
</l><l ln="15      ">The silver thread of the streamlet o'er
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;Throwing the spray.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="17      ">Her cargo was of jewels rare,
</l><l ln="18      ">All luminous, splendid and fair;
</l><l ln="19      ">The ensign of a prince was there
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;Undoubtedly.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="21      ">Methinks I saw his armor there,
</l><l ln="22      ">Brilliantly grand, superb and rare,
</l><l ln="23      ">Whose shield was beaming ev'rywhere,
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;Like a coronet.</l></stanza>
<pb n="84">
<stanza><l ln="25      ">And through the helmet of his robe
</l><l ln="26      ">Two luminous orbs lit his abode,
</l><l ln="27      ">And like the fixed stars brightly glowed
</l><l ln="28      ">&indent;Continuously.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="29      ">And near this dazzling light appears
</l><l ln="30      ">A blazing meteor beneath the spheres,
</l><l ln="31      ">Expression's guide of joy and fears
</l><l ln="32      ">&indent;Incased in pearl.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="33      ">This pearly armament's support
</l><l ln="34      ">Is cunningly built, a coral fort
</l><l ln="35      ">Compassed with ruby fleets, which float
</l><l ln="36      ">&indent;'Round there for aye.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="37      ">And when its florid portals oped,
</l><l ln="38      ">The cadence of the prince awoke
</l><l ln="39      ">The music Mother Eve evoked
</l><l ln="40      ">&indent;In Paradise.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="41      ">Then the stream, grand, masterly stream,
</l><l ln="42      ">Moved swiftly, silent and serene,
</l><l ln="43      ">The bark and its fair guide between,
</l><l ln="44      ">&indent;To run the falls.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="45      ">But still she, with her skillful hand,
</l><l ln="46      ">E'er taught the tottering craft to stand
</l><l ln="47      ">The strain and shock of the rocky strand
</l><l ln="48      ">&indent;Which lies below.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="49      ">Where the stream runs its merry race
</l><l ln="50      ">Of rapid, smooth and subtile grace,
</l><l ln="51      ">The craft leaped o'er the falls, to face
</l><l ln="52      ">&indent;The surge and whirl,</l></stanza>
<pb n="85">
<stanza><l ln="53      ">Of the deep, the grand and awful wave,
</l><l ln="54      ">Where the frothy waters toil and rave
</l><l ln="55      ">On in their course, as they engrave
</l><l ln="56      ">&indent;Their history.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="57      ">And bickers on by sunlit hills,
</l><l ln="58      ">Where Vanity Fair the passion fills,
</l><l ln="59      ">And pompous pride in the breast instills
</l><l ln="60      ">&indent;A new desire.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="61      ">Then out, and 'round the slippery curve
</l><l ln="62      ">Where bold Maturity's heights subserve
</l><l ln="63      ">The channel to deepen, and to swerve
</l><l ln="64      ">&indent;Its rapid flight.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="65      ">Then down the rugged precipice,
</l><l ln="66      ">Through the whirling pools of Error's bliss,
</l><l ln="67      ">Where the troubled waters seethe and hiss
</l><l ln="68      ">&indent;A flood of tears.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="69      ">Here, where youth's border land appears,
</l><l ln="70      ">The gallant oarsman drops his fears,
</l><l ln="71      ">And, king&hyphen;like, o'er the floods he rears
</l><l ln="72      ">&indent;His stately head.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="73      ">Then through green fields and sunny climes,
</l><l ln="74      ">Where Cupid's violin strikes the chimes
</l><l ln="75      ">Of melody's tunes and happy rhymes,
</l><l ln="76      ">&indent;The river runs.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="77      ">Till o'er its purling waters came
</l><l ln="78      ">The splash of golden oars again,
</l><l ln="79      ">Dashing the silver spray like rain
</l><l ln="80      ">&indent;From Cupid's prow.</l></stanza>
<pb n="86">
<stanza><l ln="81      ">Where Evylin sat, an angel bright,
</l><l ln="82      ">A fair, celestial angel bright,
</l><l ln="83      ">Guiding another bark of light
</l><l ln="84      ">&indent;Through Love's domain;</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="85      ">Where moon, and stars, and earth, and air
</l><l ln="86      ">Seemed covered with the mystic snare,
</l><l ln="87      ">Which Cupid throws to catch the fair
</l><l ln="88      ">&indent;Angelic thing,</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="89      ">As she sweeps down the silver stream
</l><l ln="90      ">Beneath the glow of beauty's beam,
</l><l ln="91      ">With hope's, and love's, and fancy's gleam
</l><l ln="92      ">&indent;Of wild delight,</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="93      ">Steering for that semi&hyphen;paradise,
</l><l ln="94      ">To the land where experience lies,
</l><l ln="95      ">Where truth and wisdom harmonize
</l><l ln="96      ">&indent;Youth's fervent fires.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="97      ">Here many a green isle appears,
</l><l ln="98      ">Along the stream, where the sunny years,
</l><l ln="99      ">Of conjugal life devoutly wears
</l><l ln="100    ">&indent;Contentment's crown.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="101    ">Till the stream impetuous grows,
</l><l ln="102    ">And pride, deceitful pride, blows
</l><l ln="103    ">His clarion horn and goes
</l><l ln="104    ">&indent;About the sails,</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="105    ">Of ev'ry ship which daily files,
</l><l ln="106    ">Adown the stream by the sunny isles;
</l><l ln="107    ">Where with them all fame flies and smiles
</l><l ln="108    ">&indent;Bewitchingly.</l></stanza>
<pb n="87">
<stanza><l ln="109    ">Just flies and smiles; beguiles and tries
</l><l ln="110    ">To lead all 'neath the sunny skies,
</l><l ln="111    ">With windy inconsistencies
</l><l ln="112    ">&indent;Off the Isles of Peace.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="113    ">Till Ambition comes, an oarsman dark,
</l><l ln="114    ">A stern, deceptive oarsman dark,
</l><l ln="115    ">And takes possession of the bark,
</l><l ln="116    ">&indent;And rows blindly on.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="117    ">Where all the floods become untied
</l><l ln="118    ">And pour their torrents far and wide,
</l><l ln="119    ">From mountain side to mountain side,
</l><l ln="120    ">&indent;Through the dismal swamp.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="121    ">Ambition's meed, dark discontent,
</l><l ln="122    ">And Fame's worthless emolument,
</l><l ln="123    ">So often pledged, but seldom sent,
</l><l ln="124    ">&indent;Till this good day.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="125    ">Till the splendor of the old bark's glow,
</l><l ln="126    ">Which all well knew in that long ago,
</l><l ln="127    ">Is storm&hyphen;driven so till we scarce know
</l><l ln="128    ">&indent;What 'tis or does.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="129    ">But I saw it with the billows toil,
</l><l ln="130    ">When the turbulent stream's rough turmoil
</l><l ln="131    ">Did its fair prospects taunt and foil,
</l><l ln="132    ">&indent;And roll grumbling on.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="133    ">Through bold tornadoes it had gone;
</l><l ln="134    ">I saw the rent where Calumny's storm,
</l><l ln="135    ">Swept through the sails and then hissed on
</l><l ln="136    ">&indent;Relentlessly.</l></stanza>
<pb n="88">
<stanza><l ln="137    ">But the bark was a kingly one,
</l><l ln="138    ">It weathered the storms; I saw it run
</l><l ln="139    ">Grappling with the stream and overcome
</l><l ln="140    ">&indent;The vicious winds</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="141    ">That stormed along the malignant strand,
</l><l ln="142    ">Just where looms up the goodly land
</l><l ln="143    ">Of Fame's domain and Fancy's grand
</l><l ln="144    ">&indent;Expectantcy.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="145    ">Again, I saw it sail, and sail,
</l><l ln="146    ">Proud and defiant with the gale,
</l><l ln="147    ">With hope, iron will, and nerves of mail
</l><l ln="148    ">&indent;Combatting the fates.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="149    ">Where the stream runs purling swift and strong
</l><l ln="150    ">In its murmuring, liquid song
</l><l ln="151    ">Breaking hope, and will, and nerves along
</l><l ln="152    ">&indent;The cataract.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="153    ">And still the craft sped with the wave.
</l><l ln="154    ">On the crest of the billows laved,
</l><l ln="155    ">Nor heeded the omnivorous grave
</l><l ln="156    ">&indent;That yawned below</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="157    ">Where the river bold grew deep and wide;
</l><l ln="158    ">Till it so placidly seemed to glide,
</l><l ln="159    ">That its deceptive waves belied
</l><l ln="160    ">&indent;Its rapid flight.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="161    ">To the grand and deep old ocean wide,
</l><l ln="162    ">Rolling in all its majestic pride,
</l><l ln="163    ">Until the crest of its hoar tide
</l><l ln="164    ">&indent;The river met.</l></stanza>
<pb n="89">
<stanza><l ln="165    ">There it eddied as if it would be still,
</l><l ln="166    ">And the oarsman, infirm and ill,
</l><l ln="167    ">Furled his sails, surrendered his will,
</l><l ln="168    ">&indent;And crossed his oars.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="169    ">For that ruby bulwark, strong and bold,
</l><l ln="170    ">And those luminous orbs&mdash;now cold&mdash;
</l><l ln="171    ">Swing to and fro, a ruin old,
</l><l ln="172    ">&indent;Sacked at last by Time.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="173    ">Who stands Death's oceanic mien!
</l><l ln="174    ">However mute the winds, bright the sheen,
</l><l ln="175    ">Or peacefully lulled the marine
</l><l ln="176    ">&indent;Which decoys him?</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="177    ">And if the zephyrs do play low,
</l><l ln="178    ">Light, soft and smooth the deep sea o'er
</l><l ln="179    ">They but waft the bark and its cargo
</l><l ln="180    ">&indent;Into port.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>
<pb n="90">
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200265073</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Beadle, Samuel Alfred<sombiog>232</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead>AFTERWARD.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200265073</ID><A1>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</A1><T1>AFTERWARD.</T1><PBL>W. A. Scott</PBL><Y1>1912</Y1><T2>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</attpoet><attidref>C2040235</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>C2040235</attidref><attdbase>African-American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>AFTERWARD.</mainhead><volhead>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1899</attpubn1><attpubn2>1899</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>232</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">I'm</hi> all alone in the world, now,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;My bonnie love has flown;
</l><l ln="3        ">My heart's an empty void, now,
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;Where the wreck of joy is strown;
</l><l ln="5        ">For o'er her grave, the tombs between,
</l><l ln="6        ">The grass is growing green.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="7        ">I'm sad tonight! I did not know
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;How dear she was to me;
</l><l ln="9        ">How fervent was her passion's glow,
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;Her love's sincerity;
</l><l ln="11      ">Till o'er her grave, the tombs between,
</l><l ln="12      ">The grass was growing green.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="13      ">I would I could see her face again,
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;That furrowed face of care,
</l><l ln="15      ">That I might woo away the pain
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;My coldness chiseled there;
</l><l ln="17      ">And lie for her the tombs between,
</l><l ln="18      ">Where the grass is growing green.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="19      ">I somehow feel, since she has gone,
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;That negligence is crime:
</l><l ln="21      ">That I am guilty of this wrong
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;To my eyelids brings the brine:
</l><l ln="23      ">Since she lies cold the tombs between,
</l><l ln="24      ">Where the grass is growing green.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>
<pb n="91">
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200265074</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Beadle, Samuel Alfred<sombiog>232</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead>AGE'S REJOINDER.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200265074</ID><A1>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</A1><T1>AGE'S REJOINDER.</T1><PBL>W. A. Scott</PBL><Y1>1912</Y1><T2>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</attpoet><attidref>C2040236</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>C2040236</attidref><attdbase>African-American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>AGE'S REJOINDER.</mainhead><volhead>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1899</attpubn1><attpubn2>1899</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>232</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">I would</hi> not live always:
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;I ask but to stay&rdquo;
</l><l ln="3        ">In this vain world of shadows
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;Just another day;
</l><l ln="5        ">By that other day I mean
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;Three score years and ten,
</l><l ln="7        ">Then, perhaps, I'll take my leave
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;Willingly, of men.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="9        ">Yet, if it suits my Lord
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;To lengthen the thread
</l><l ln="11      ">That tethers me to earth's shores,
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;A few more years instead,
</l><l ln="13      ">Contentedly I'll plod on&mdash;
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;With my crutch and cane
</l><l ln="15      ">Bear the weight of four score years,
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;And not complain.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="17      ">Live always? Of course not!
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;But I'd like to see
</l><l ln="19      ">My span of years reeling down
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;To the century.
</l><l ln="21      ">&ldquo;What about my absent friends,
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;And rheumatic foe?&rdquo;
</l><l ln="23      ">I'll forget those, this endure,
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;A year and a day more.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>
<pb n="99">
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200265075</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Beadle, Samuel Alfred<sombiog>232</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead>LINES TO MR. &wblank;</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200265075</ID><A1>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</A1><T1>LINES TO MR. &wblank;</T1><PBL>W. A. Scott</PBL><Y1>1912</Y1><T2>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</attpoet><attidref>C2040237</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>C2040237</attidref><attdbase>African-American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>LINES TO MR. &wblank;</mainhead><volhead>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1899</attpubn1><attpubn2>1899</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>232</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">Friend</hi>, must we part and part forever?
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;The spell that bound our hearts is broke&mdash;
</l><l ln="3        ">Did I say &ldquo;friend&rdquo;? Excuse me,&mdash;brother;
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;I would the word I'd never spoke.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="5        ">And brother, too, I should forget,
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;Since you the sacred tie would spurn
</l><l ln="7        ">T' indulge the passions which have met
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;'Round our friendship's broken urn.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="9        ">And yet it's hard and passing strange
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;That one brief hour should sever us;
</l><l ln="11      ">And that a broken pledge should change
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;Hearts for a thing so odious.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="13      ">But I had learned to trust you so&mdash;
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;Thought you so far above mankind,
</l><l ln="15      ">So noble, and so true&mdash;when, lo!
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;Deception's wand strikes you blind.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="17      ">Blind to all that we used to be,
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;Blind to all that we ought to be,
</l><l ln="19      ">Blind still to yourself and me&mdash;
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;Blind even to vile treachery.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="21      ">But should fortune e'er desert you,
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;Fate mark for you a rugged lot,
</l><l ln="23      ">For what you ought to be I'll serve you,
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;And of your treachery think not.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>
<pb n="100">
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200265076</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Beadle, Samuel Alfred<sombiog>232</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead>STRIKE FOR EQUAL RIGHTS.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200265076</ID><A1>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</A1><T1>STRIKE FOR EQUAL RIGHTS.</T1><PBL>W. A. Scott</PBL><Y1>1912</Y1><T2>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</attpoet><attidref>C2040238</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>C2040238</attidref><attdbase>African-American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>STRIKE FOR EQUAL RIGHTS.</mainhead><volhead>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1899</attpubn1><attpubn2>1899</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>232</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">Think</hi> of the price of liberty,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Think of the lash and slavery,
</l><l ln="3        ">Of lynch rule and its massacre
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;And strike for equal rights.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="5        ">Say, must we longer trust the law,
</l><l ln="6        ">Class&hyphen;enacted to hide the flaw
</l><l ln="7        ">Of the crimson hand that strikes to awe
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;And terrorize us into slaves?</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="9        ">Let him who trembles or has fears,
</l><l ln="10      ">When the cowardly mob appears,
</l><l ln="11      ">Receive a coward's meed and tears,
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;Death and a piece of hemp.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="13      ">Where the American who would be
</l><l ln="14      ">A renegade to liberty;
</l><l ln="15      ">Because of fear would turn and flee,
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;When duty calls him here.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="17      ">He should be yoked and bound for aye,
</l><l ln="18      ">As long as night succeeds the day&mdash;
</l><l ln="19      ">For liberty can only stay,
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;The meed of valiant men.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="21      ">He who fears not the mob's alarm:
</l><l ln="22      ">To him who would the traitors storm,
</l><l ln="23      ">And fell them with a valiant arm,
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;Behold a freeman's meed!</l></stanza>
<pb n="101">
<stanza><l ln="25      ">Come the valiant, and come the brave,
</l><l ln="26      ">Come all except the abject slave&mdash;
</l><l ln="27      ">Let him fall in a bondman's grave&mdash;
</l><l ln="28      ">&indent;And strike for liberty!</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="29      ">Come all the law abiding, come,
</l><l ln="30      ">Where'er throughout the earth you roam,
</l><l ln="31      ">And strike for native land and home,
</l><l ln="32      ">&indent;For God and sacred life.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200265077</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Beadle, Samuel Alfred<sombiog>232</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead>WHILE THE WALTZ IS ON.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200265077</ID><A1>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</A1><T1>WHILE THE WALTZ IS ON.</T1><PBL>W. A. Scott</PBL><Y1>1912</Y1><T2>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</attpoet><attidref>C2040239</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>C2040239</attidref><attdbase>African-American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>WHILE THE WALTZ IS ON.</mainhead><volhead>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1899</attpubn1><attpubn2>1899</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>232</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">Ere</hi> the banquet's over, love,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;And the stars are gone;
</l><l ln="3        ">Before the garlands wither, love,
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;While the waltz is on,
</l><l ln="5        ">Whisper softly in my ear
</l><l ln="6        ">Love's melody, my dear.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="7        ">While the waltz is on, my dear,
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;And the music's roll
</l><l ln="9        ">Echoes through the hall so clear,
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;So happy makes the soul,
</l><l ln="11      ">As we reel and turn and whirl
</l><l ln="12      ">Say yes, my bonny girl.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="13      ">Ere the dance is done, sweetheart,
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;Before the music dies,
</l><l ln="15      ">Make me glad, before we part,
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;Complete my paradise;
</l><l ln="17      ">Just before the music's gone,
</l><l ln="18      ">And while the waltz is on.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>
<pb n="102">
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200265078</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Beadle, Samuel Alfred<sombiog>232</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead>THE MUSIC OF THE RAIN.</mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200265078</ID><A1>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</A1><T1>THE MUSIC OF THE RAIN.</T1><PBL>W. A. Scott</PBL><Y1>1912</Y1><T2>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</attpoet><attidref>C2040240</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>C2040240</attidref><attdbase>African-American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>THE MUSIC OF THE RAIN.</mainhead><volhead>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1899</attpubn1><attpubn2>1899</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>232</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">There's</hi> music in the rain,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;As on the roof it drops,
</l><l ln="3        ">&indent;&indent;And its monotonous tap, tap
</l><l ln="4        ">Beats on the window pane;
</l><l ln="5        ">&indent;Or murmuring it stops
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;&indent;A moment on the dripping eaves.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="7        ">There's music in the rain
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;When it falls the leaves among,
</l><l ln="9        ">&indent;&indent;And spatters in the viney nooks
</l><l ln="10      ">And sparkles on the grain;
</l><l ln="11      ">&indent;All earth has found a tongue,
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;&indent;And its loud hallelujahs ring.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="13      ">Oh! the music of the rain,
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;See it comes pouring down,
</l><l ln="15      ">&indent;&indent;Bright and joyous o'er field and plain,
</l><l ln="16      ">While its golden currents drain
</l><l ln="17      ">&indent;The smooth and verdured lawn,
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;&indent;And then run bickering to the main.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="19      ">There's music in the rain,
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;When all the winds arise,
</l><l ln="21      ">&indent;&indent;And livid lightning marks the path
</l><l ln="22      ">Of the dread hurricane;
</l><l ln="23      ">&indent;While in the clouded skies
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;&indent;Old thunder beats the martial airs.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="25      ">There's music in the rain
</l><pb n="103">
<l ln="26      ">&indent;When all the winds are still,
</l><l ln="27      ">&indent;&indent;When lightning's flash and thunder's roll
</l><l ln="28      ">Are stilled and mute again;
</l><l ln="29      ">&indent;And you feel the heart's thrill
</l><l ln="30      ">&indent;&indent;When the storm cloud goes racking by.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="31      ">There's music in the rain
</l><l ln="32      ">&indent;When the clouds are clearing off,
</l><l ln="33      ">&indent;&indent;And sunny beams come struggling through
</l><l ln="34      ">The silver of the rain,
</l><l ln="35      ">&indent;Where hope's arch stands alof'
</l><l ln="36      ">&indent;&indent;In the reflux of the storms.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200265079</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Beadle, Samuel Alfred<sombiog>232</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead>IDA.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200265079</ID><A1>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</A1><T1>IDA.</T1><PBL>W. A. Scott</PBL><Y1>1912</Y1><T2>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</attpoet><attidref>C2040241</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>C2040241</attidref><attdbase>African-American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>IDA.</mainhead><volhead>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1899</attpubn1><attpubn2>1899</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>232</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">She</hi> is a woman, bright and trim,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Of five and twenty years,
</l><l ln="3        ">Who trips along with pleasure
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;And spends her smiles for tears.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="5        ">Her hair retains its raven hue,
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;Her sparkling eye its fire;
</l><l ln="7        ">But her heart is sad, discordant,
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;A strung, but tuneless lyre.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="9        ">For she staked her all on conquest
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;Of the voluptuous host,
</l><l ln="11      ">With society's devotees
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;Bet high, played long and lost.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="13      ">She's wiser now than yesterday,
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;At last she spurns the dream
</l><l ln="15      ">That women were made for pleasure,
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;And men are what they seem.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>
<pb n="111">
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200265080</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Beadle, Samuel Alfred<sombiog>232</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead>THE GOLDEN ROD.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200265080</ID><A1>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</A1><T1>THE GOLDEN ROD.</T1><PBL>W. A. Scott</PBL><Y1>1912</Y1><T2>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</attpoet><attidref>C2040242</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>C2040242</attidref><attdbase>African-American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>THE GOLDEN ROD.</mainhead><volhead>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1899</attpubn1><attpubn2>1899</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>232</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">There</hi> is a calm and solemn air
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Along the road, by garden fair,
</l><l ln="3        ">By rushing stream, and ev'rywhere
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;The sear and yellow leaf's aglow.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="5        ">The foliage is growing old;
</l><l ln="6        ">All through the verdure gleams the gold;
</l><l ln="7        ">The rose is turning into mold;
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;But golden rod stands ev'rywhere.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="9        ">O'er the lea and across the mead,
</l><l ln="10      ">And far away where the cattle feed,
</l><l ln="11      ">There blows the yellow crested reed,
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;The autumnal queen of flowers.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="13      ">Its golden crown along the way,
</l><l ln="14      ">Sways back and forth, and seems to say,
</l><l ln="15      ">&ldquo;I am fair Flora's Queen today,
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;And the wind's my messenger boy.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="17      ">&ldquo;And further on the wind's low wail
</l><l ln="18      ">Proclaims my reign along the dale,
</l><l ln="19      ">Till the tired harvester drops his flail
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;And hails me queen of the flowers.&rdquo;</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>
<pb n="112">
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200265081</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Beadle, Samuel Alfred<sombiog>232</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead>YELLOW JACK OF '97.</mainhead> <attbytes>5Kb</attbytes><volhead>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200265081</ID><A1>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</A1><T1>YELLOW JACK OF '97.</T1><PBL>W. A. Scott</PBL><Y1>1912</Y1><T2>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</attpoet><attidref>C2040243</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>C2040243</attidref><attdbase>African-American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>YELLOW JACK OF '97.</mainhead><volhead>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>5Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1899</attpubn1><attpubn2>1899</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>232</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">With</hi> a shudder still I remember
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;The alarm of Yellow Jack:
</l><l ln="3        ">Sent out in the daily number,
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;Of the &ldquo;Times&hyphen;Democrat.&rdquo;</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="5        ">Also the &ldquo;Daily Picayune&rdquo;
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;Made the dreaded tidings known;
</l><l ln="7        ">The paper venders caught the tune
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;And heralded it around the town.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="9        ">&ldquo;Here's your &lsquo;Daily Picayune,&rsquo;&rdquo;
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;And &ldquo;Here's your &lsquo;Times&hyphen;Democrat!&rsquo;&rdquo;
</l><l ln="11      ">&ldquo;Paper, sir, &lsquo;Daily Picayune,&rsquo;
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;All about the Yellow Jack!&rdquo;</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="13      ">&ldquo;At Ocean Springs and Scranton, sir,
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;Biloxi and ev'rywhere
</l><l ln="15      ">Along the coast&mdash;&lsquo;Picayune,&rsquo; sir?
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;All about the fever there!</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="17      ">&ldquo;There 'tis, sir! a catastrophe,
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;Strikes our business interest square,
</l><l ln="19      ">And leaves us a wreck in mid sea,
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;With fever and despair.&rdquo;</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="21      ">&ldquo;If it's fever, it's dengue,
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;Or malaria from lack
</l><l ln="23      ">Of cleanliness, in a few
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;Coast towns. It's not Yellow Jack,&rdquo;</l></stanza>
<pb n="113">
<stanza><l ln="25      ">Said all the doctors, looking wise.
</l><l ln="26      ">&indent;But the restless feeling grew,
</l><l ln="27      ">And all the people, with glaring eyes,
</l><l ln="28      ">&indent;And ashen lips, said &ldquo;It's true!&rdquo;</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="29      ">From the start business stopped, congealed,
</l><l ln="30      ">&indent;And strong men gathered the crowd
</l><l ln="31      ">About the public streets, to feel
</l><l ln="32      ">&indent;The business pulse, sigh aloud;</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="33      ">And then to troop it out of town:
</l><l ln="34      ">&indent;For their fancy paints so well,
</l><l ln="35      ">Until it kinder brings them down,
</l><l ln="36      ">&indent;To unwholesome views of (&wblank;) Well&mdash;</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="37      ">You understand; roasting scenes in that
</l><l ln="38      ">&indent;Sultry country where the swell
</l><l ln="39      ">Epidemic fiend, grim Yellow Jack,
</l><l ln="40      ">&indent;The conductor acts so well.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="41      ">You talk of being panic struck,
</l><l ln="42      ">&indent;Routed friend and all of that;
</l><l ln="43      ">You should see the bulletin stuck
</l><l ln="44      ">&indent;To the alarm of Yellow Jack.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="45      ">For yellow fever 'larms from press
</l><l ln="46      ">&indent;And newsboys, can clear the earth
</l><l ln="47      ">With inflated yells of distress
</l><l ln="48      ">&indent;In twenty minutes without death.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="49      ">And then the faithful few, who stand
</l><l ln="50      ">&indent;At duty's post; because
</l><l ln="51      ">They cannot escape, understand,
</l><l ln="52      ">&indent;Prohibitory laws.</l></stanza>
<pb n="114">
<stanza><l ln="53      ">They quarantine the empty void
</l><l ln="54      ">&indent;With a mailed guard so well,
</l><l ln="55      ">That 'twould terrorize the alloid
</l><l ln="56      ">&indent;Visage of the host of Hell.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="57      ">Then gnaws the formidable thought,
</l><l ln="58      ">&indent;Quarantined away from home:
</l><l ln="59      ">This experience so dearly bought,
</l><l ln="60      ">&indent;So vividly paints our own:</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="61      ">Till we see the ghost of all our hopes
</l><l ln="62      ">&indent;Floating down the yellow stream;
</l><l ln="63      ">Our empty homes along the copse
</l><l ln="64      ">&indent;And grim Yellow Jack between.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="65      ">And hear the stroke of the sturdy oar,
</l><l ln="66      ">&indent;The surge of the awful wave;
</l><l ln="67      ">As Yellow Jack trips our loved ones o'er&mdash;
</l><l ln="68      ">&indent;The druggist into the grave.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>
<pb n="115">
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200265082</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Beadle, Samuel Alfred<sombiog>232</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead>YOUTH'S HOME AND MOTHER.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200265082</ID><A1>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</A1><T1>YOUTH'S HOME AND MOTHER.</T1><PBL>W. A. Scott</PBL><Y1>1912</Y1><T2>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</attpoet><attidref>C2040244</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>C2040244</attidref><attdbase>African-American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>YOUTH'S HOME AND MOTHER.</mainhead><volhead>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1899</attpubn1><attpubn2>1899</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>232</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">Down</hi> the long flight of years,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;With the fleet sweep of time,
</l><l ln="3        ">Our memory still bears
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;On the one place sublime,
</l><l ln="5        ">Of all that earth holds of joy and of mirth,
</l><l ln="6        ">And that place, friend, is the place of our birth.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="7        ">The gay may dazzle the eye,
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;For a time brightly blaze
</l><l ln="9        ">Then dimly burn and die;
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;Then 'tis we fix and gaze
</l><l ln="11      ">On all that earth holds of joy and of mirth,
</l><l ln="12      ">Down the dim vista ways of long ago.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="13      ">Friendship may fail and fly
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;Off by night and our joy,
</l><l ln="15      ">With the breath of morning die;
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;Naught be ours but alloy,
</l><l ln="17      ">And all that earth holds of joy and of mirth,
</l><l ln="18      ">Youth's home and mother and her sterling worth</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="19      ">Deep as is the ocean's brine,
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;Love will trace her epitaph,
</l><l ln="21      ">Along the strand of time;
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;Where stands the biograph
</l><l ln="23      ">Of all the nation's worth, its cares and mirth
</l><l ln="24      ">In mother's love, and faith, and works, and home.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="25      ">These will blaze, burn and glow
</l><pb n="116">
<l ln="26      ">&indent;Until the end of time;
</l><l ln="27      ">Till again we meet, and know
</l><l ln="28      ">&indent;Our parting was sublime!
</l><l ln="29      ">Till we meet and know, where the ransomed go,
</l><l ln="30      ">Up the endless aisles of paradise.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200265083</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Beadle, Samuel Alfred<sombiog>232</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead>INNOCENCE ASLEEP.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200265083</ID><A1>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</A1><T1>INNOCENCE ASLEEP.</T1><PBL>W. A. Scott</PBL><Y1>1912</Y1><T2>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</attpoet><attidref>C2040245</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>C2040245</attidref><attdbase>African-American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>INNOCENCE ASLEEP.</mainhead><volhead>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1899</attpubn1><attpubn2>1899</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>232</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">A fair</hi> dark&hyphen;eyed lassie was she,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Her thirteenth summer passed,
</l><l ln="3        ">Who pursuing blue&hyphen;eyed daisy,
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;Herself had over&hyphen;tasked;
</l><l ln="5        ">And fell asleep in the meadow,
</l><l ln="6        ">Where the wildest flowers blow.
</l><l ln="7        ">I read the dreams upon her face.
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;Through dimples in her cheek,
</l><l ln="9        ">And smiles which trace the subtle grace
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;Of innocence asleep.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="11      ">&ldquo;I was dreaming,&rdquo; she made reply,
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;A blush her whole physique,
</l><l ln="13      ">When my kerchief fell upon the fly
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;That lit upon her cheek;
</l><l ln="15      ">Hard by the laughing brooklet's sheen
</l><l ln="16      ">Caught the poise of her face between,
</l><l ln="17      ">Demurring pout and sly grimace,
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;Through her dishelved hair;
</l><l ln="19      ">&indent;As she stood there an angel fair
</l><l ln="20      ">With innocence awake.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>
<pb n="117">
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200265084</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Beadle, Samuel Alfred<sombiog>232</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead>THE RAPE OF THE FLOWERS.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200265084</ID><A1>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</A1><T1>THE RAPE OF THE FLOWERS.</T1><PBL>W. A. Scott</PBL><Y1>1912</Y1><T2>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</attpoet><attidref>C2040246</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>C2040246</attidref><attdbase>African-American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>THE RAPE OF THE FLOWERS.</mainhead><volhead>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1899</attpubn1><attpubn2>1899</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>232</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">Wails</hi>, wails, wails,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">The wind from its ice bound thrones;
</l><l ln="3        ">Along the path it trails,
</l><l ln="4        ">And whistles and roams
</l><l ln="5        ">Across the gray old fields.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="6        ">Sweeps, sweeps, sweeps,
</l><l ln="7        ">Together the falling leaves,
</l><l ln="8        ">And up the hillside leaps
</l><l ln="9        ">Through the naked trees;
</l><l ln="10      ">There shrieks, and roars, and storms;</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="11      ">And shakes, shakes, shakes
</l><l ln="12      ">His mantle that holds the snows
</l><l ln="13      ">Till the mute and silent flake,
</l><l ln="14      ">Its purity throws
</l><l ln="15      ">O'er all the dreary earth.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="16      ">Then drives along the rain,
</l><l ln="17      ">The cold benumbing rain;
</l><l ln="18      ">Across the dreary plain,
</l><l ln="19      ">Blows the hurricane
</l><l ln="20      ">And freezes o'er the snow.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="21      ">Till all is hard, cold ice,
</l><l ln="22      ">Transparent, luminous ice,
</l><l ln="23      ">Whose dumb but stern device
</l><l ln="24      ">The rivers entice
</l><l ln="25      ">To stand at last congealed.</l></stanza>
<pb n="118">
<stanza><l ln="26      ">Weeping now the angels go,
</l><l ln="27      ">Since Winter's seductive hand
</l><l ln="28      ">Polluted lovely Flo,
</l><l ln="29      ">And his grim command
</l><l ln="30      ">Her nectary fills with ice.</l></stanza>
<stanza><l ln="31      ">At the kiss of hoar frost,
</l><l ln="32      ">The radiant angel swooned,
</l><l ln="33      ">Of dire grief died, and lost
</l><l ln="34      ">Her beautiful bloom&mdash;
</l><l ln="35      ">Her rare ethereal bloom.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem>
<comhd2><idref>Z200265085</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Beadle, Samuel Alfred<sombiog>232</sombiog></somauth><poemicon> <mainhead>TO A FLOWER ON A CORPSE.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200265085</ID><A1>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</A1><T1>TO A FLOWER ON A CORPSE.</T1><PBL>W. A. Scott</PBL><Y1>1912</Y1><T2>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Beadle, Samuel Alfred</attpoet><attidref>C2040247</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>C2040247</attidref><attdbase>African-American Poetry</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>TO A FLOWER ON A CORPSE.</mainhead><volhead>Sketches from Life in Dixie (1899)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1899</attpubn1><attpubn2>1899</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>232</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>
<firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">Ah</hi>, thou beautiful embellishment of earth,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;By dew, and rain, and dutiful spring hurled,
</l><l ln="3        ">&indent;A thing of loveliness, into this world
</l><l ln="4        ">Of woe, and discord, and the cruel dearth
</l><l ln="5        ">That blights our desires, and turns our hearth
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;Into a charnel house; nor king, nor earl,
</l><l ln="7        ">Nor wit, can provoke the sad heart to mirth,
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;Where our hopes all end and our colors furl.
</l><l ln="9        ">Fit emblem of man's transient stage art thou;
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;This morn beheld thee delightfully fair,
</l><l ln="11      ">Full of fragrance, pleasingly sweet; but now,
</l><l ln="12      ">This eve, thy withered form sleeps on the prow
</l><l ln="13      ">&indent;Of that barque grim Death is launching out there,
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;In the omnivorous sea of dispair.</l></poem>
</div2>
